17
00:01:02,800 --> 00:01:07,700
REVOLUTION OS

18
00:01:09,400 --> 00:01:11,600
For most its short, but colorful history,

19
00:01:11,600 --> 00:01:13,600
the computer industry has been dominated

20
00:01:13,600 --> 00:01:15,500
by the Windows operating system.

21
00:01:15,500 --> 00:01:17,500
But that could soon change,

22
00:01:17,500 --> 00:01:20,400
as Windows faces a strong challenge from Linux

23
00:01:21,800 --> 00:01:23,500
Silicon Valley has long been the place

24
00:01:23,500 --> 00:01:25,500
to develop new technology,

25
00:01:25,800 --> 00:01:29,300
start new companies and get really rich.

26
00:01:29,400 --> 00:01:31,800
Now The Valley is the front line in a revolution

27
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:34,700
fighting for that most politically incorrect of ideas:

28
00:01:35,200 --> 00:01:36,500
individual freedom

29
00:01:37,200 --> 00:01:38,800
Day and night, a loose confederation of

30
00:01:39,000 --> 00:01:41,000
hackers and programmers zaps bits pieces of

31
00:01:41,100 --> 00:01:43,800
computer code around the world as it builds the tools

32
00:01:44,200 --> 00:01:46,000
to set computer users free

33
00:01:46,300 --> 00:01:48,600
using open information and the free exchange of technology

34
00:01:48,600 --> 00:01:50,000
to achieve its goals.

35
00:01:50,000 --> 00:01:52,600
This revolution began in the 1980's with

36
00:01:52,600 --> 00:01:55,300
the Free Software Movement and GNU project.

37
00:01:55,300 --> 00:01:57,000
And now is most commonly associated

38
00:01:57,300 --> 00:02:00,600
with Linux and the Open Source Movement.

39
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:03,600
What is Linux?

40
00:02:03,600 --> 00:02:06,000
We do have one sector that taking off today.

41
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:08,100
It is the Linux-related sector.

42
00:02:08,100 --> 00:02:10,200
And I thought this might be a good opportunity to say,

43
00:02:10,500 --> 00:02:12,200
"What is Linux?"

44
00:02:12,400 --> 00:02:13,400
And I'll answer this question for you.

45
00:02:13,500 --> 00:02:14,500
Many of you probably already know,

46
00:02:14,500 --> 00:02:16,000
but There are 12 million users out there

47
00:02:16,300 --> 00:02:19,600
A computer Operating System developed by hundreds of

48
00:02:19,600 --> 00:02:21,500
programmers collaborating on the Internet

49
00:02:21,500 --> 00:02:23,400
A challenge to Microsoft Windows NT

50
00:02:23,500 --> 00:02:25,000
Very popular for its speed

51
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:27,300
and so this's what the craze is about

52
00:02:29,000 --> 00:02:31,200
To kind of explain what Linux is you have to

53
00:02:31,200 --> 00:02:33,200
explain what an Operating System is

54
00:02:33,200 --> 00:02:35,700
And... the thing about Operating System is you, I mean...

55
00:02:35,700 --> 00:02:38,400
you're never ever supposed to see it.

56
00:02:38,400 --> 00:02:40,100
Because...

57
00:02:40,100 --> 00:02:42,300
nobody really uses an Operating System,

58
00:02:42,700 --> 00:02:45,500
people use... programs... on their computer

59
00:02:45,500 --> 00:02:47,500
And the only mission in life

60
00:02:47,900 --> 00:02:51,500
of an operating system is to help those programs run.

61
00:02:51,800 --> 00:02:55,100
So an operating system never does anything on its own

62
00:02:55,300 --> 00:02:57,700
It's only waiting for the programs to

63
00:02:57,700 --> 00:03:00,000
ask for certain resources or,

64
00:03:00,300 --> 00:03:03,600
or, ask for a certain file on the disk

65
00:03:03,800 --> 00:03:05,500
or ask for the programs to

66
00:03:05,500 --> 00:03:07,300
connect them to the outside world.

67
00:03:07,500 --> 00:03:10,100
And then the operating system comes, steps in and then

68
00:03:10,100 --> 00:03:13,700
tries to make it easy for people to write programs

69
00:03:13,700 --> 00:03:17,000
And, What is Open Source?

70
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:20,000
Open Source is a way for people to collaborate

71
00:03:20,300 --> 00:03:25,700
on software without being encumbered by all of the problems of intellectual property,

72
00:03:25,700 --> 00:03:30,200
having to negotiate contracts every time you buy a piece of software,

73
00:03:30,500 --> 00:03:32,800
have a lot of lawyers involved.

74
00:03:32,800 --> 00:03:36,000
In general, we just wanna get the software to work

75
00:03:36,400 --> 00:03:37,800
and we want be able to have

76
00:03:37,800 --> 00:03:40,900
people contribute fixes to that, etc..

77
00:03:41,800 --> 00:03:44,000
So we sort of sacrifice some of

78
00:03:44,000 --> 00:03:45,900
the intellectual property rights

79
00:03:46,000 --> 00:03:48,500
and just let the whole world use the software

80
00:03:50,500 --> 00:03:51,800
Before there could be Linux

81
00:03:51,900 --> 00:03:55,200
There was Richard Stallman and the Free Software Movement.

82
00:03:55,500 --> 00:03:58,200
They think of Richard Stallman as the...

83
00:03:59,300 --> 00:04:02,000
great philosopher, right.

84
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:03,800
And think of me as the engineer

85
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:08,400
Richard Stallman is the founding father of the Free Software Movement.

86
00:04:08,800 --> 00:04:12,000
Through his efforts to build the GNU Operating System.

87
00:04:12,100 --> 00:04:15,900
He created the legal, philosophical and technological foundation

88
00:04:15,900 --> 00:04:17,800
for the Free Software Movement.

89
00:04:17,800 --> 00:04:19,400
Without these contributions,

90
00:04:19,400 --> 00:04:21,900
it's unlikely that Linux and Open Source

91
00:04:21,900 --> 00:04:24,000
would have evolved in to their current forms today

92
00:04:24,700 --> 00:04:28,700
I joined the MIT Artificial Intelligence Lab in 1971,

93
00:04:29,000 --> 00:04:33,000
I joined... a thriving community of hackers,

94
00:04:33,700 --> 00:04:35,000
people who loved programming,

95
00:04:35,000 --> 00:04:38,300
loved exploring the what they could do with computers.

96
00:04:38,500 --> 00:04:41,700
And they had developed a complete Operating System,

97
00:04:41,700 --> 00:04:44,200
entirely written there.

98
00:04:44,300 --> 00:04:46,800
And I became one of the team, that

99
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:50,400
continued to improve the Operating System, adding new capabilities

100
00:04:50,400 --> 00:04:54,400
That was my job, and I loved it, we all loved it. That's why we were doing it.

101
00:04:55,000 --> 00:04:58,100
And [clears throat] we called our system

102
00:04:58,100 --> 00:05:00,600
"the Incompatible Time Sharing System"

103
00:05:01,200 --> 00:05:02,600
which is an example of the

104
00:05:02,600 --> 00:05:03,600
playful spirit

105
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:05,900
which defines a hacker.

106
00:05:06,100 --> 00:05:09,200
Hackers are people who enjoy playful cleverness.

107
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:12,500
Well, it first started going wrong

108
00:05:12,500 --> 00:05:16,000
as the outside world started pressuring us to have passwords.

109
00:05:16,100 --> 00:05:19,300
We didn't have any passwords on our computer.

110
00:05:19,500 --> 00:05:21,500
And the reason was that the hackers

111
00:05:21,500 --> 00:05:23,800
who'd originally designed the system

112
00:05:23,800 --> 00:05:29,700
realized that passwords were a way the administrators could control all the users.

113
00:05:29,800 --> 00:05:32,200
And they didn't want to build tools

114
00:05:32,500 --> 00:05:35,900
you know, locks and keys for the administrators to control them,

115
00:05:36,200 --> 00:05:38,300
so they just didn't do it. They left that out

116
00:05:39,300 --> 00:05:42,500
And we had the philosophy that whoever sitting at the computer

117
00:05:42,600 --> 00:05:45,000
should be able to do whatever he wants

118
00:05:45,500 --> 00:05:50,500
and somebody else who was there yesterday shouldn't be controlling what you do today

119
00:05:50,500 --> 00:05:54,300
When they put passwords onto one of the machines at MIT

120
00:05:55,500 --> 00:05:57,500
I and bunch of other hackers didn't like it,

121
00:05:57,500 --> 00:06:01,500
I decided to try a subversive sort of hack. [clears throat]

122
00:06:02,300 --> 00:06:04,400
I figured out how to decode the passwords,

123
00:06:04,400 --> 00:06:07,800
so by looking at the database of encoded passwords

124
00:06:07,800 --> 00:06:11,300
I could figure out what each person would actually type to login

125
00:06:11,800 --> 00:06:14,200
And so I sent messages to people, saying,

126
00:06:14,500 --> 00:06:17,600
"Hello? I see that you've chosen the password mumble,

127
00:06:17,800 --> 00:06:20,000
whatever it was. How about if you do as I do

128
00:06:20,500 --> 00:06:22,500
just type Enter for your password

129
00:06:22,500 --> 00:06:25,500
it's much shorter, much easier to type".

130
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:29,500
And... of course with this message I was

131
00:06:29,500 --> 00:06:33,000
implicitly telling them the security was really just a joke.

132
00:06:33,300 --> 00:06:37,300
Anyway, but in addition I was letting them in on this hack.

133
00:06:37,800 --> 00:06:41,500
And eventually, A fifth of all the users on that computer joined me

134
00:06:41,600 --> 00:06:45,000
in using just Enter as their passwords.

135
00:06:45,000 --> 00:06:48,100
[ Where did the ideas that lead to what is now called Open Source world?

136
00:06:48,200 --> 00:06:50,200
How did that begin? Who began that? ]

137
00:06:50,300 --> 00:06:54,300
It actually began with the start of computers because at that time

138
00:06:54,500 --> 00:06:57,400
software was just passed around between people

139
00:06:57,500 --> 00:07:02,400
And I think it was only like in the lates 70's or early 80's

140
00:07:03,000 --> 00:07:06,500
That people started really closing up their software,

141
00:07:06,500 --> 00:07:09,700
And saying, "No, you can never get a look at the source code.

142
00:07:10,000 --> 00:07:13,300
You can't change the software even if it's necessary

143
00:07:13,400 --> 00:07:16,300
for you to fix it, for your own application"

144
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:21,000
And... um, you can actually blame some of that on Microsoft,

145
00:07:21,200 --> 00:07:25,200
They are one of the real pioneers of the proprietary software model.

146
00:07:25,600 --> 00:07:27,800
In the mid 1970's, a group of hackers

147
00:07:27,900 --> 00:07:32,500
and computer hobbyist in Silicon Valley formed the "Homebrew Computer Club".

148
00:07:33,000 --> 00:07:36,500
In the club January 31, 1976 newsletter,

149
00:07:36,500 --> 00:07:39,200
Bill Gates of the recently formed Microsoft,

150
00:07:39,500 --> 00:07:41,000
wrote an open letter to the community

151
00:07:41,500 --> 00:07:47,600
where he made a point by point argument for the relatively new concept of proprietary software

152
00:07:47,800 --> 00:07:52,200
up to that point, the practice of computer users had been to freely pass around software

153
00:07:52,500 --> 00:07:55,000
with not much thought given to its ownership

154
00:07:55,500 --> 00:07:58,100
Known as An Open Letter to Hobbyists, Bill Gates writes,

155
00:07:58,500 --> 00:08:00,800
"To me the most critical thing in the hobby market right now

156
00:08:00,900 --> 00:08:03,900
is the lack of good software courses, books and software itself.

157
00:08:04,000 --> 00:08:07,100
Without good software and an owner who understands programming,

158
00:08:07,300 --> 00:08:09,300
A hobby computer is wasted.

159
00:08:09,300 --> 00:08:12,000
Will quality software be written for the hobby market?

160
00:08:12,400 --> 00:08:14,900
Gates goes on to write, "The feedback we have gotten from

161
00:08:14,900 --> 00:08:18,300
the hundreds of people who say they are using BASIC has all been positive.

162
00:08:18,300 --> 00:08:20,500
Two surprising things are apparent, however.

163
00:08:20,500 --> 00:08:23,500
1) Most of these "users" never bought BASIC, and

164
00:08:23,500 --> 00:08:26,500
2) The amount of royalties we have received from sales to hobbyists

165
00:08:26,500 --> 00:08:30,500
makes the time spent on of Altair BASIC worth less than 2 dollars an hour

166
00:08:30,500 --> 00:08:31,700
Why is this?

167
00:08:31,700 --> 00:08:34,200
As the majority of hobbyists must be aware,

168
00:08:34,200 --> 00:08:36,300
most of you steal your software.

169
00:08:36,300 --> 00:08:39,200
Hardware must be paid for but software is something to share.

170
00:08:39,200 --> 00:08:41,500
Who cares if the people who worked on it get paid?

171
00:08:41,500 --> 00:08:42,900
Is this fair?

172
00:08:42,900 --> 00:08:45,000
One thing you don't do by stealing software

173
00:08:45,000 --> 00:08:47,500
is get back at MITS for some problem you may have had

174
00:08:47,500 --> 00:08:49,600
MITS doesn't make money selling software.

175
00:08:49,600 --> 00:08:52,600
One thing you do do is prevent good software from being written.

176
00:08:53,000 --> 00:08:55,300
Who can afford to do professional work for nothing?

177
00:08:55,600 --> 00:08:58,300
What hobbyist can put 3-man years into programming,

178
00:08:58,300 --> 00:09:01,900
finding all bugs, documenting his product and distribute it for free?

179
00:09:01,900 --> 00:09:02,800
The fact is,

180
00:09:02,800 --> 00:09:06,400
no one besides us has invested a lot of money in hobby software.

181
00:09:06,400 --> 00:09:09,000
What about the guys who resell Altair BASIC?

182
00:09:09,000 --> 00:09:11,300
Aren't they making money on hobby software?

183
00:09:11,300 --> 00:09:14,800
Yes, but those who have been reported to us may lose in the end.

184
00:09:14,800 --> 00:09:16,900
They are the ones who give hobbyists a bad name,

185
00:09:16,900 --> 00:09:20,300
and should be kicked out of any club meeting they show up at.

186
00:09:20,300 --> 00:09:23,200
I would appreciate letters from anyone who wants to pay up,

187
00:09:23,200 --> 00:09:25,000
or has a suggestion or comment.

188
00:09:25,000 --> 00:09:29,000
Signed Bill Gates, General partner, Micro-Soft.

189
00:09:29,400 --> 00:09:33,100
In the late 70's and early 1980's, Richard Stallman was

190
00:09:33,100 --> 00:09:36,400
doing Artificial Intelligence research and coding

191
00:09:36,400 --> 00:09:39,000
at the MIT Artificial Intelligence Lab.

192
00:09:39,000 --> 00:09:41,300
Richard had a number of negative experiences

193
00:09:41,300 --> 00:09:43,300
during that period which soured him

194
00:09:43,300 --> 00:09:45,400
on the whole idea of commercial software.

195
00:09:45,400 --> 00:09:47,000
[ such as? ]

196
00:09:47,000 --> 00:09:51,000
uh... some company wanted to work on and wanted to fix was locked up.

197
00:09:51,700 --> 00:09:55,700
and he couldn't get the company that owned on the code to let him fix it

198
00:09:56,400 --> 00:09:58,500
even though it would have been to their advantage to do so.

199
00:09:58,500 --> 00:10:01,400
And that put me into a moral dilemma, you see?

200
00:10:01,500 --> 00:10:07,100
Because to get one of the modern computers of the day, which was the early 80's,

201
00:10:07,600 --> 00:10:10,400
you would have to get a proprietory operating system.

202
00:10:10,500 --> 00:10:13,400
The developers of those systems didn't share with other people,

203
00:10:13,500 --> 00:10:15,500
Instead they tried to control the users,

204
00:10:15,600 --> 00:10:17,400
dominate the users, restrict them.

205
00:10:17,900 --> 00:10:20,000
Say, if to get the system,

206
00:10:20,100 --> 00:10:23,500
you have to sign a  promise you won't share with anybody else.

207
00:10:23,600 --> 00:10:27,400
And to me that was essentially a promise to be a bad person,

208
00:10:27,400 --> 00:10:29,100
to betray the rest of the world,

209
00:10:29,200 --> 00:10:33,100
cut myself off from society from a cooperating community.

210
00:10:34,300 --> 00:10:38,300
And I had already experienced what happened when other people did that to us,

211
00:10:38,300 --> 00:10:39,800
when they refused to share with us.

212
00:10:39,900 --> 00:10:42,500
because they had signed these contracts.

213
00:10:42,600 --> 00:10:44,400
And it hurt the whole lab,

214
00:10:44,500 --> 00:10:47,200
it kept us from doing useful things before.

215
00:10:47,300 --> 00:10:49,600
So I just wasn't going to do that.

216
00:10:49,700 --> 00:10:53,700
I thought,"This is wrong! I am not going to live this way"

217
00:10:53,900 --> 00:10:57,900
And from experiences like this he developed a profound hostility

218
00:10:58,000 --> 00:11:00,600
to the idea of intellectual property and software.

219
00:11:00,700 --> 00:11:04,300
He eventually acted this out by founding the Free Software Foundation.

220
00:11:04,400 --> 00:11:08,900
So, I looked for another alternative and I realized:

221
00:11:09,000 --> 00:11:10,500
I was an operating system developer.

222
00:11:10,600 --> 00:11:14,300
If I were to develop another operating system.

223
00:11:14,500 --> 00:11:18,100
And then as the author, encourage everyone to share it.

224
00:11:18,200 --> 00:11:21,900
Say, everyone, " You come and get it, use this, form a new community"

225
00:11:22,900 --> 00:11:27,200
Not only could I gave myself a way to keep using computers without

226
00:11:27,300 --> 00:11:30,500
betraying other people, but I'd give it to everybody else, too.

227
00:11:30,600 --> 00:11:33,500
Everybody would have a way out of that moral dilemma

228
00:11:35,000 --> 00:11:38,300
And so I realized this was what I had to do with my life.

229
00:11:38,700 --> 00:11:42,700
I actually began the project in January of 1984.

230
00:11:42,800 --> 00:11:45,500
That's when I resigned for my job at MIT

231
00:11:45,600 --> 00:11:49,400
to start developing the GNU operating system.

232
00:11:50,400 --> 00:11:53,700
Now I should explain the name GNU is a hack.

233
00:11:53,900 --> 00:11:56,700
Because it's a recursive acronym.

234
00:11:57,100 --> 00:12:00,100
It stands for "GNU's Not Unix".

235
00:12:00,200 --> 00:12:03,300
You see so the "G" in "GNU" stands for "GNU".

236
00:12:03,300 --> 00:12:05,400
And what the name means is

237
00:12:05,400 --> 00:12:09,900
I was developing a system that was like the Unix operating system,

238
00:12:09,900 --> 00:12:12,300
but was not the Unix operating system.

239
00:12:12,300 --> 00:12:13,800
This was a different system.

240
00:12:13,800 --> 00:12:16,200
We would have to write it completely from scratch

241
00:12:16,200 --> 00:12:18,100
because Unix was proprietory.

242
00:12:18,200 --> 00:12:20,000
We were forbidden to share Unix,

243
00:12:20,100 --> 00:12:23,700
We couldn't use Unix. It was useless for a community.

244
00:12:23,800 --> 00:12:27,300
So we had to write a replacement for it.

245
00:12:28,900 --> 00:12:30,100
Throughout the 1980s,

246
00:12:30,200 --> 00:12:32,700
as Richard Stallman was building the GNU project,

247
00:12:32,900 --> 00:12:36,300
computer scientists from the University of California at Berkeley

248
00:12:36,400 --> 00:12:38,700
were developing their own free operating system.

249
00:12:39,000 --> 00:12:41,500
Known as Berkeley Unix, or BSD,

250
00:12:41,600 --> 00:12:45,500
it was based upon the Unix kernel which had been licensed from AT&T.

251
00:12:45,600 --> 00:12:50,300
However, due to legal problems with AT&T and fragmentation of the source code,

252
00:12:50,500 --> 00:12:54,100
hackers and other non-institutional users were slow to adopt it

253
00:12:54,300 --> 00:12:58,300
Well, Unix consisted of a large number of separate programs

254
00:12:58,700 --> 00:13:00,400
that communicated with each other.

255
00:13:00,500 --> 00:13:03,400
So we just had to replace these programs one by one.

256
00:13:03,500 --> 00:13:07,200
So what I started doing was writing a replacement for one program,

257
00:13:07,300 --> 00:13:09,100
and then another, and then another,

258
00:13:09,200 --> 00:13:10,900
and then people started joining me,

259
00:13:11,000 --> 00:13:14,600
because I published an announcement inviting other people to join me

260
00:13:14,700 --> 00:13:16,300
to help write these programs.

261
00:13:16,600 --> 00:13:24,000
And uh... and by around 1991, we had replaced practically all of them.

262
00:13:24,500 --> 00:13:25,800
[ What were some of the programs that you ... ]

263
00:13:25,900 --> 00:13:29,000
Well... we had to... to have a complete system,

264
00:13:29,100 --> 00:13:32,700
you need to have a kernel, which is the program that

265
00:13:32,800 --> 00:13:35,600
allocates resources to all the other programs,

266
00:13:35,800 --> 00:13:39,100
you need a compiler, which translates a program

267
00:13:39,200 --> 00:13:44,500
from readable source code that programmers can understand into numbers,

268
00:13:44,600 --> 00:13:48,900
mysterious numbers that the computer can actually run.

269
00:13:49,000 --> 00:13:51,500
you need other programs that go with the compiler to help do this job.

270
00:13:51,500 --> 00:13:52,600
you need a debugger.

271
00:13:52,700 --> 00:13:54,300
you need a text editor.

272
00:13:54,400 --> 00:13:55,500
you need text formatters.

273
00:13:55,600 --> 00:13:57,400
you need mailers...

274
00:13:57,500 --> 00:13:58,800
you need lots and lots of things.

275
00:13:58,900 --> 00:14:02,500
There are hundreds of programs in a Unix-like operating system.

276
00:14:02,900 --> 00:14:04,500
I saw Stallman's announcement.

277
00:14:04,600 --> 00:14:07,900
Actually I met him in February of 1987.

278
00:14:08,000 --> 00:14:12,500
He came to give a five-day tutorial on Emacs at our company.

279
00:14:12,600 --> 00:14:15,200
And during the day he would explain

280
00:14:15,300 --> 00:14:17,400
new ways to think about Emacs

281
00:14:17,500 --> 00:14:20,500
and ways to extend it, enhance it, and to use the Emacs source code

282
00:14:21,100 --> 00:14:22,400
uh, for better or worse.

283
00:14:22,500 --> 00:14:25,700
But in the evening, he was busily working on this compiler,

284
00:14:25,800 --> 00:14:28,100
and he had not yet released it to the public,

285
00:14:28,200 --> 00:14:31,800
so he was uh, being a little bit uh, careful about

286
00:14:31,900 --> 00:14:34,300
who, who got to see the source code.

287
00:14:34,400 --> 00:14:37,800
But I was very eager, and when he first announced it in June,

288
00:14:37,900 --> 00:14:39,500
I downloaded it immediately.

289
00:14:39,700 --> 00:14:41,100
I, I played with it.

290
00:14:41,200 --> 00:14:43,400
I got some, some pointers from him.

291
00:14:43,600 --> 00:14:45,200
And when I sent the source code back to him,

292
00:14:45,300 --> 00:14:46,500
he was very,

293
00:14:46,600 --> 00:14:51,300
uh, actually amazed that how quickly I was able to ramp up on his technology.

294
00:14:51,500 --> 00:14:52,300
Whenever we worked on something at Stanford or in the university,

295
00:14:52,300 --> 00:14:56,300
Whenever we worked on something at Stanford or in the university,

296
00:14:56,400 --> 00:14:58,200
we would get, mostly at the time

297
00:14:58,300 --> 00:15:02,200
we were working off machines from Digital Equipment or Sun, mostly Sun.

298
00:15:02,400 --> 00:15:03,900
Whenever we would get a Sun machine,

299
00:15:04,100 --> 00:15:08,500
the first thing we would do is we would spend literally days

300
00:15:08,600 --> 00:15:12,600
downloading GNU free software from the Internet,

301
00:15:12,700 --> 00:15:15,100
building it and installing it on that Sun machine.

302
00:15:15,300 --> 00:15:18,800
The crucial thing about GNU is that it's free software.

303
00:15:19,200 --> 00:15:22,700
And Free Software refers not to price, but to freedom.

304
00:15:22,900 --> 00:15:25,200
So think of free speech, not free beer.

305
00:15:26,200 --> 00:15:28,500
The freedoms that I am talking about

306
00:15:28,500 --> 00:15:31,500
are the freedoms to make changes if you want to,

307
00:15:31,600 --> 00:15:34,300
or hire somebody else to make changes for you

308
00:15:34,400 --> 00:15:36,500
if you're using a software for your business,

309
00:15:36,600 --> 00:15:40,300
to redistribute copies, to share with other people,

310
00:15:40,400 --> 00:15:43,500
and to make improvements and publish them

311
00:15:43,600 --> 00:15:46,500
so that other people can get the benefit of them, too.

312
00:15:46,600 --> 00:15:50,400
And those are the freedoms that distinguish free software from non-free software.

313
00:15:50,700 --> 00:15:54,500
These are the freedoms that enable people to form a community.

314
00:15:54,600 --> 00:15:56,100
If you don't have all these freedoms,

315
00:15:56,100 --> 00:15:58,900
you're being divided and dominated by somebody.

316
00:15:59,900 --> 00:16:03,000
My first experience contributing to free software

317
00:16:03,000 --> 00:16:07,000
came in late 1989, early 1990.

318
00:16:07,200 --> 00:16:10,200
I was working as a graduate student at Stanford University

319
00:16:10,400 --> 00:16:12,600
on Computer Aided Design tools.

320
00:16:12,700 --> 00:16:14,800
One of the pieces I needed was a tool

321
00:16:14,900 --> 00:16:16,500
called a parser generator.

322
00:16:16,800 --> 00:16:18,800
Well, the Free Software Foundation

323
00:16:18,900 --> 00:16:22,300
under Richard Stallman created a great tool called "bison".

324
00:16:22,500 --> 00:16:26,400
I needed a tool that worked with C++. Bison worked with C.

325
00:16:26,900 --> 00:16:30,100
I modified bison to create something called "bison++".

326
00:16:30,200 --> 00:16:32,700
And it's a tremendous feeling of empowerment

327
00:16:32,800 --> 00:16:35,900
be able to take a piece of software that was available

328
00:16:36,000 --> 00:16:40,500
and create what you needed in a very short piece of time by modifying it.

329
00:16:40,700 --> 00:16:43,100
I put it back on the Internet

330
00:16:43,200 --> 00:16:44,900
and I was amazed at the number of people

331
00:16:45,000 --> 00:16:46,900
that picked it up and started using it.

332
00:16:47,000 --> 00:16:51,000
In fact, I remember going to, uh job interviews,

333
00:16:51,300 --> 00:16:54,100
I, at various times, considered just going out getting a job.

334
00:16:54,300 --> 00:16:56,100
And I'd gone to a job interview.

335
00:16:56,200 --> 00:16:57,600
And I was talking to one of the people,

336
00:16:57,700 --> 00:17:00,500
and I started asking them about what tools they used,

337
00:17:00,600 --> 00:17:03,000
and they said, "Gee, we used bison++!"

338
00:17:03,100 --> 00:17:05,400
and I said, "Oh, I am the author of bison++!"

339
00:17:05,600 --> 00:17:10,100
Free Software generally does have a copyright.

340
00:17:10,200 --> 00:17:12,800
It does have an owner.

341
00:17:12,900 --> 00:17:14,000
And it has a license.

342
00:17:14,100 --> 00:17:15,900
It is not public domain.

343
00:17:16,000 --> 00:17:18,600
If we put the software in the public domain,

344
00:17:18,700 --> 00:17:21,900
somebody else would be able to make a little bit of changes

345
00:17:22,000 --> 00:17:24,900
and turn that into a proprietory software package,

346
00:17:25,000 --> 00:17:27,800
which means that the users would be running our software,

347
00:17:27,900 --> 00:17:30,800
but they wouldn't have freedom to cooperate and share.

348
00:17:31,500 --> 00:17:35,200
To prevent that, we use a technique called "Copyleft".

349
00:17:35,500 --> 00:17:38,700
The idea of Copyleft is that it's "Copyright" flipped over.

350
00:17:39,500 --> 00:17:41,200
And what we do is, we say,

351
00:17:41,300 --> 00:17:43,200
this software is copyrighted

352
00:17:43,300 --> 00:17:47,600
and we, the authors give you permission to redistribute copies,

353
00:17:47,700 --> 00:17:49,200
we give you permission to change,

354
00:17:49,300 --> 00:17:50,900
we give you permission to add to it.

355
00:17:51,000 --> 00:17:52,700
But when you redistribute it,

356
00:17:52,800 --> 00:17:56,500
it has to be under these terms, no more and no less.

357
00:17:56,600 --> 00:17:58,800
So that whoever gets it from you

358
00:17:58,900 --> 00:18:04,200
also gets the freedom to cooperate with other people, if he wants to.

359
00:18:04,300 --> 00:18:07,800
And then, in this way everywhere the software goes,

360
00:18:07,900 --> 00:18:09,500
the freedom goes, too.

361
00:18:09,600 --> 00:18:11,900
And it becomes an inalienable right

362
00:18:13,000 --> 00:18:15,600
to cooperate with other people and form a community.

363
00:18:15,800 --> 00:18:19,100
[ And so, what is that? the license? what was that... ]

364
00:18:19,200 --> 00:18:21,200
Well, Copyleft being a general idea,

365
00:18:21,300 --> 00:18:24,300
in order to use it, you have to have specific example.

366
00:18:24,400 --> 00:18:28,100
The specific example we use for most GNU software packages

367
00:18:28,200 --> 00:18:31,100
is the GNU General Public License,

368
00:18:31,200 --> 00:18:35,200
a particular document in legalese which accomplishes this job.

369
00:18:35,500 --> 00:18:38,200
A lot of other people use that same license, for example,

370
00:18:38,300 --> 00:18:41,700
Linus Torvalds uses that license for Linux as well.

371
00:18:42,700 --> 00:18:46,200
Well, the license I use is the GNU General Public License.

372
00:18:46,300 --> 00:18:48,200
That's the one Richard Stallman wrote.

373
00:18:48,300 --> 00:18:52,200
And I think it is really astounding contribution.

374
00:18:52,300 --> 00:18:56,300
Uh, it's one of the few software licenses that was written

375
00:18:56,600 --> 00:19:00,000
from the standpoint of the community rather than

376
00:19:00,100 --> 00:19:03,900
from the standpoint of um, protecting a company

377
00:19:04,000 --> 00:19:09,500
or um, as is the case with MIT and BSD license

378
00:19:09,700 --> 00:19:13,400
performing the goals of a government grant program.

379
00:19:13,500 --> 00:19:16,500
Uh, and the GPL is really unique in that.

380
00:19:16,600 --> 00:19:20,000
It's not just a license. It's a whole philosophy that,

381
00:19:20,100 --> 00:19:23,100
I think, motivated the open source definition.

382
00:19:23,200 --> 00:19:27,500
I don't hide that a lot of what I do came from Stallman.

383
00:19:31,900 --> 00:19:35,900
A crucial step in the growth of GNU/Linux and the Free Software movement

384
00:19:36,000 --> 00:19:39,600
was the creation of businesses based upon the software and philosophy.

385
00:19:39,800 --> 00:19:42,300
Grown zero for the beginning of the business phase

386
00:19:42,400 --> 00:19:45,500
was the Electronics Research Lab at Stanford University.

387
00:19:45,800 --> 00:19:49,100
Known as ERL, the lab was the place for the first GNU

388
00:19:49,200 --> 00:19:51,500
and Linux business founder inspiration.

389
00:19:51,600 --> 00:19:53,600
So right here was where ERL was.

390
00:19:54,100 --> 00:19:57,200
That would have been the entrance over there next to the uh,

391
00:19:57,300 --> 00:19:59,600
electrical engineering McCullough building.

392
00:19:59,700 --> 00:20:03,500
As you walk in, you come in, you walk down the hallway, down here.

393
00:20:04,500 --> 00:20:07,600
My office would have been about, about here.

394
00:20:07,700 --> 00:20:11,000
and then right across the hall, from that was Michael Tiemann's office.

395
00:20:11,700 --> 00:20:15,700
Michael Tiemann took uh.. and started a company, Cygnus Software

396
00:20:15,700 --> 00:20:20,600
with the idea was to sell consulting and services around the GNU Free Software

397
00:20:20,600 --> 00:20:23,000
and, well Michael's done very well with Cygnus.

398
00:20:23,000 --> 00:20:27,000
Well uh, I spend a lot of time working out uh,

399
00:20:27,000 --> 00:20:29,000
how we were going to make money

400
00:20:29,000 --> 00:20:31,000
and in the original GNU manifesto

401
00:20:31,000 --> 00:20:34,000
which is the last chapter of the GNU Emacs manual.

402
00:20:34,000 --> 00:20:36,000
Stallman proposed a number of different

403
00:20:36,000 --> 00:20:37,800
possible ways to make money.

404
00:20:37,800 --> 00:20:39,800
From the beginning of the Free Software movement

405
00:20:39,800 --> 00:20:41,000
I had the idea that there's

406
00:20:41,000 --> 00:20:43,000
room in it for business to be done.

407
00:20:43,000 --> 00:20:45,700
One of the advantages of Free Software is that, there's

408
00:20:45,700 --> 00:20:49,000
a free market for any kind of service or support.

409
00:20:49,000 --> 00:20:51,000
So if you are using software in your business,

410
00:20:51,000 --> 00:20:53,000
and you want good support,

411
00:20:53,000 --> 00:20:56,000
you have a choice of people to go to for it,

412
00:20:56,000 --> 00:20:58,000
you have a choice of businesses... that

413
00:20:58,000 --> 00:21:01,000
are in the business of providing you with support.

414
00:21:01,000 --> 00:21:03,000
So they are going to have to in general give you

415
00:21:03,000 --> 00:21:06,000
good support or you go to somebody else.

416
00:21:06,000 --> 00:21:08,000
With proprietory software,

417
00:21:08,300 --> 00:21:11,000
support is a monopoly, there is one company,

418
00:21:11,000 --> 00:21:13,600
typically, that has the source code

419
00:21:13,600 --> 00:21:15,500
and only they can give you support

420
00:21:16,100 --> 00:21:19,300
so typically, you are at the mercy of a monopoly.

421
00:21:19,300 --> 00:21:21,600
That's the case, for example with Microsoft.

422
00:21:21,600 --> 00:21:24,900
So no wonder the support is so bad.

423
00:21:24,900 --> 00:21:26,500
The benefits of Free Software were

424
00:21:26,500 --> 00:21:29,200
tremendous but the cost of supporting it internally

425
00:21:29,800 --> 00:21:31,800
uh, and made managers very very nervous and

426
00:21:31,800 --> 00:21:35,500
so the fundamental idea I had was if we can build a model

427
00:21:35,500 --> 00:21:39,500
that could deliver two to four times the support

428
00:21:39,500 --> 00:21:43,000
and uh, and uh, and hand holding capability

429
00:21:43,000 --> 00:21:45,100
that an internal engineer could provide.

430
00:21:45,100 --> 00:21:48,100
And we could do it at 1/2 to 1/4 of the cost

431
00:21:48,100 --> 00:21:50,300
that would meet the test of whether or not

432
00:21:50,300 --> 00:21:51,900
people would actually buy.

433
00:21:51,900 --> 00:21:54,400
And by about the Fall of that year, we had

434
00:21:54,400 --> 00:21:56,300
all the things worked out about who

435
00:21:56,300 --> 00:21:57,900
needed on the technical team, what

436
00:21:57,900 --> 00:21:59,800
the terms the sale would be, what

437
00:21:59,800 --> 00:22:01,600
the key price point were, and we

438
00:22:01,600 --> 00:22:05,600
actually received our incorporation in Nov of 1989.

439
00:22:06,200 --> 00:22:08,800
One of the most difficult things in starting our company

440
00:22:08,800 --> 00:22:10,400
was actually finding a name for it.

441
00:22:10,400 --> 00:22:13,000
I explained this to one of my friends

442
00:22:13,000 --> 00:22:14,400
"we're having difficulty"

443
00:22:14,400 --> 00:22:16,900
and he returned an e-mail message

444
00:22:16,900 --> 00:22:20,800
that basically just had a bunch of words with the name "GNU" in it.

445
00:22:20,800 --> 00:22:25,600
And "Cygnus" was the one that looked least obnoxious and least obscene.

446
00:22:26,100 --> 00:22:28,600
I can say very clearly that Cygnus

447
00:22:28,900 --> 00:22:32,600
was the first business that specialized in Free Software.

448
00:22:32,800 --> 00:22:36,100
Cygnus supported Free Software,

449
00:22:36,100 --> 00:22:40,100
filled a very essential niche because we had this great software,

450
00:22:40,100 --> 00:22:44,100
you could get it for nothing but you couldn't get support - they made their money

451
00:22:44,300 --> 00:22:46,200
by charging for support.

452
00:22:46,200 --> 00:22:49,900
The GNU project started by building a toolkit,

453
00:22:49,900 --> 00:22:54,800
uh, basic development tools such as a C compiler, a debugger, a text-editor,

454
00:22:55,100 --> 00:22:58,500
and uh, other necessary apparatus.

455
00:22:58,500 --> 00:23:03,000
And their intention was eventually to develop a kernel to sit underneath those

456
00:23:03,200 --> 00:23:05,600
and be the center of the operating system.

457
00:23:05,600 --> 00:23:09,400
By about 1990 they had successfully developed that toolkit,

458
00:23:09,400 --> 00:23:13,400
and it was in wide use on great many variants of Unix.

459
00:23:13,500 --> 00:23:16,100
But there was still no free kernel.

460
00:23:16,100 --> 00:23:20,100
The kernel happened to be one of the last things we started to do

461
00:23:20,400 --> 00:23:22,400
and we had started it not long before.

462
00:23:23,400 --> 00:23:26,400
And that's when Linus Torvalds came along.

463
00:23:26,400 --> 00:23:29,700
"Lin-us" or "Line-us"? What's the exact, do you prefer the pronunciation?

464
00:23:30,000 --> 00:23:32,600
um.. When I speak Swedish it's "Lee-nus";

465
00:23:32,600 --> 00:23:35,000
when I speak Finnish it's "Leen-ous";

466
00:23:35,000 --> 00:23:36,800
when I speak English it's "Line-us".

467
00:23:36,800 --> 00:23:39,600
And I really don't care how people pronounce my name.

468
00:23:39,600 --> 00:23:42,400
But "Linux" is always "Linux".

469
00:23:42,400 --> 00:23:46,800
He developed a kernel, and got it working faster than we got ours working,

470
00:23:47,400 --> 00:23:49,900
and got it to work very nicely and solidly.

471
00:23:49,900 --> 00:23:51,800
His kernel is called "Linux".

472
00:23:52,300 --> 00:23:55,500
The initial goal was my very personal goal

473
00:23:55,500 --> 00:23:59,100
to be able to run a similar environment on my computer

474
00:23:59,500 --> 00:24:03,300
that I had grown used to at, at the university computers.

475
00:24:03,900 --> 00:24:09,300
And I could not find anything that suited me for that.

476
00:24:09,700 --> 00:24:13,400
So having been doing computers for all my life basically.

477
00:24:13,400 --> 00:24:16,500
At that point I decided that I'll do my own.

478
00:24:17,000 --> 00:24:21,000
Most of the inspiration early on came from, from SunOS

479
00:24:21,600 --> 00:24:25,900
which was what um, I was using at the university at the time.

480
00:24:25,900 --> 00:24:27,000
[ Which University? ]

481
00:24:27,000 --> 00:24:28,700
University of Helsinki in Finland.

482
00:24:29,600 --> 00:24:34,100
From 1991 to about 1993 was really

483
00:24:34,400 --> 00:24:36,700
I guess the infancy period of Linux.

484
00:24:36,700 --> 00:24:40,400
That was when it was still only alpha or beta quality;

485
00:24:40,400 --> 00:24:42,800
it was relatively unstable.

486
00:24:42,800 --> 00:24:45,600
Although, even then it was a good deal more stable

487
00:24:45,600 --> 00:24:49,600
than a lot of what are now called "production" operating systems.

488
00:24:49,600 --> 00:24:53,600
Linus used the traditional tried-and-true method of writing one program

489
00:24:54,500 --> 00:24:56,500
that does the job,

490
00:24:56,700 --> 00:24:58,800
and he got it to work.

491
00:24:58,800 --> 00:25:02,500
quickly in fact faster than I would have thought was possible.

492
00:25:02,500 --> 00:25:05,500
The term for it is "monolithic",

493
00:25:05,500 --> 00:25:13,400
which means that basically the OS itself is one entity, indivisible.

494
00:25:15,100 --> 00:25:17,400
uh, while in the microkernel,

495
00:25:17,400 --> 00:25:19,900
the, the operating system kernel is actually

496
00:25:21,600 --> 00:25:24,700
uh, just a collection of servers that

497
00:25:24,700 --> 00:25:27,500
do different things and then they have a common protocol

498
00:25:27,500 --> 00:25:29,700
for doing communication between themselves.

499
00:25:30,200 --> 00:25:35,800
[ So why is that... the GNU project that's had so much lead-time, that's been doing this,

500
00:25:35,800 --> 00:25:39,100
Why...Why is it that he was able to kinda come in at the tail end so to speak ]

501
00:25:39,100 --> 00:25:44,800
Well we actually started the GNU Hurd not long before he started Linux.

502
00:25:45,700 --> 00:25:49,700
And it happened though we chose a design that's a very advanced design

503
00:25:50,300 --> 00:25:52,300
in terms of the power gives you

504
00:25:52,300 --> 00:25:54,900
but also turns out to be very hard to debug.

505
00:25:55,600 --> 00:26:01,300
We decided to divide up the kernel which traditionally had been one program,

506
00:26:01,300 --> 00:26:03,600
to divide it up into a lot of smaller programs

507
00:26:03,600 --> 00:26:07,600
that would send messages to each other asynchronously to, to communicate.

508
00:26:09,600 --> 00:26:13,500
The problem is that, that style of programming

509
00:26:13,500 --> 00:26:15,800
has a great deal of potential for bugs,

510
00:26:15,800 --> 00:26:18,700
which are often very hard to figure out because they depend on...

511
00:26:18,700 --> 00:26:26,100
does this program send this message before or after this one sends that message...

512
00:26:26,300 --> 00:26:31,300
And the result was: it took us years to get the thing to work.

513
00:26:32,300 --> 00:26:35,700
[ What is Linux's relationship to the GNU project? ]

514
00:26:36,700 --> 00:26:43,100
Well there's relationships to GNU on kind of multiple levels.

515
00:26:43,600 --> 00:26:47,600
One is just the philosophical level of thinking that

516
00:26:48,200 --> 00:26:50,700
"making your source open is a good idea".

517
00:26:51,300 --> 00:26:55,300
When Linus developed the kernel he wasn't doing it for the GNU project.

518
00:26:55,300 --> 00:26:56,800
He did it independently.

519
00:26:56,800 --> 00:27:00,200
And he released it independently and we didn't know about it.

520
00:27:00,200 --> 00:27:02,500
But some of the people who did know about it

521
00:27:02,500 --> 00:27:05,000
decided to look for what else they could find

522
00:27:05,000 --> 00:27:08,300
to put together with that kernel to make a whole system.

523
00:27:08,300 --> 00:27:12,300
They looked around, and lo and behold everything they needed was already available.

524
00:27:12,500 --> 00:27:13,500
They looked around, and lo and behold everything they needed was already available.

525
00:27:13,800 --> 00:27:15,600
"What good fortune!" they thought.

526
00:27:15,600 --> 00:27:17,900
But actually there was no chance about it.

527
00:27:17,900 --> 00:27:21,900
They had found all the pieces of the GNU system which was missing just the kernel,

528
00:27:22,700 --> 00:27:24,600
so when they put all that together

529
00:27:24,600 --> 00:27:28,600
really they were fitting Linux into the gap in the GNU system.

530
00:27:29,200 --> 00:27:30,400
But they didn't know that.

531
00:27:30,800 --> 00:27:34,800
There's a lot of these programs

532
00:27:35,500 --> 00:27:38,600
um, done by the Free Softwares Foundation,

533
00:27:38,600 --> 00:27:40,800
and done by other people like Linux.

534
00:27:40,800 --> 00:27:44,800
And there's a symbiosis between Linux and the programs

535
00:27:44,900 --> 00:27:48,700
that the programs run on Linux and at the same time

536
00:27:48,700 --> 00:27:51,100
and they take the advantage of Linux as a platform,

537
00:27:51,100 --> 00:27:54,700
while Linux takes the advantage of the programs

538
00:27:54,700 --> 00:27:56,700
by just being able to use them.

539
00:27:56,700 --> 00:27:58,300
[ What...What programs? ]

540
00:27:58,700 --> 00:28:00,100
umm...

541
00:28:00,100 --> 00:28:03,100
The main one is actually the GNU C Compiler.

542
00:28:03,700 --> 00:28:07,300
Which... Without a C compiler it would not have been possible

543
00:28:07,300 --> 00:28:13,500
to make Linux or most of the open progress available.

544
00:28:14,500 --> 00:28:16,700
Linux uses the GPL,

545
00:28:16,700 --> 00:28:21,400
and I agree with a kind of philosophy behind the GPL.

546
00:28:22,500 --> 00:28:27,200
That said the GPL itself is not a very pretty document

547
00:28:27,200 --> 00:28:31,800
which is probably just because no lawyerese can ever be very pretty.

548
00:28:37,800 --> 00:28:41,800
I'd been playing around with Linux for actually

549
00:28:42,000 --> 00:28:45,300
late '92 or early '93 for about a year.

550
00:28:45,300 --> 00:28:49,900
before I decided that it was to the point where actually had everything that I needed

551
00:28:50,200 --> 00:28:52,300
to really replace a Sun Workstation.

552
00:28:52,300 --> 00:28:56,300
And I was looking for a way to have a Unix workstation at home

553
00:28:56,400 --> 00:29:00,400
at the time we used Sun Sparc Stations in the office at Stanford.

554
00:29:01,900 --> 00:29:04,400
Those machines cost us about 7,000 dollars.

555
00:29:04,400 --> 00:29:06,900
Now I desperately wanted a Unix machine at home!

556
00:29:06,900 --> 00:29:09,600
There's always a this thought you get as a graduate student

557
00:29:09,600 --> 00:29:10,900
"Gee... if I could work at home!

558
00:29:10,900 --> 00:29:12,800
Then I would be so much more productive,

559
00:29:12,800 --> 00:29:15,900
I would graduate sooner because I would finish my thesis sooner"

560
00:29:16,500 --> 00:29:20,000
Well, Well, is it true? Well, you can judge.

561
00:29:20,000 --> 00:29:23,800
You know most people end up spending a lot of their time

562
00:29:23,800 --> 00:29:25,300
becoming more productive so that

563
00:29:25,300 --> 00:29:28,500
they ever actually worked on their thesis they'd finish it in a day.

564
00:29:28,500 --> 00:29:30,200
It takes a while sometimes.

565
00:29:30,200 --> 00:29:32,500
So I decided that I wanted a Unix machine at home.

566
00:29:32,500 --> 00:29:36,500
And I went out there I was able to use Linux together with the PC.

567
00:29:36,700 --> 00:29:40,500
For about 2,000 dollars, I put together a system.

568
00:29:40,500 --> 00:29:43,400
That was one and a half to two times faster

569
00:29:43,400 --> 00:29:46,100
than that 7,000 dollars Sun Sparc Station.

570
00:29:46,100 --> 00:29:47,800
It was absolutely amazing.

571
00:29:47,800 --> 00:29:50,800
I had one and a half to two times the speed,

572
00:29:50,800 --> 00:29:53,500
at a third to fourth the price.

573
00:29:53,500 --> 00:29:54,800
Light bulbs went off.

574
00:29:54,800 --> 00:29:57,000
I knew there was an opportunity here.

575
00:29:57,000 --> 00:30:01,000
This was the chance to really do something better than what Sun has done

576
00:30:01,100 --> 00:30:03,700
around Open Source and Linux.

577
00:30:04,100 --> 00:30:07,300
I called it Linux originally as working name.

578
00:30:07,300 --> 00:30:10,800
And that was just because "Linus"

579
00:30:10,800 --> 00:30:12,000
and the "X" has to be there.

580
00:30:12,000 --> 00:30:14,100
It's Unix. It's like a law.

581
00:30:15,400 --> 00:30:18,000
And...what happened was that...

582
00:30:18,000 --> 00:30:21,800
I initially thought that I can't call it Linux publicly,

583
00:30:21,800 --> 00:30:24,100
because it is just too egotistical.

584
00:30:24,100 --> 00:30:26,400
And that was before I had a big ego. Right?

585
00:30:26,400 --> 00:30:30,700
They thought they were taking a whole bunch of components putting them around Linux

586
00:30:31,400 --> 00:30:34,400
So they ended up calling the whole thing "A Linux System"

587
00:30:35,000 --> 00:30:37,100
and somehow that term caught on.

588
00:30:37,100 --> 00:30:38,600
And the result is

589
00:30:38,600 --> 00:30:42,600
there are now ten million people using

590
00:30:42,600 --> 00:30:44,100
this variant of the GNU system...

591
00:30:44,100 --> 00:30:46,400
the GNU/Linux operating system.

592
00:30:46,800 --> 00:30:48,500
And most of them don't know it.

593
00:30:48,800 --> 00:30:52,800
[ Some people advocate it be described as GNU/Linux.

594
00:30:53,200 --> 00:30:56,300
I mean what's your thought on that? I would say, justify or... ]

595
00:30:56,300 --> 00:31:01,600
Well, I think it's justified but it is justified if you actually make GNU distribution of Linux.

596
00:31:02,000 --> 00:31:09,100
The same way that I think that Red Hat Linux is fine or SuSE Linux, or Debian Linux.

597
00:31:10,000 --> 00:31:13,000
Uh, because if you actually make your own distribution of Linux

598
00:31:13,000 --> 00:31:14,800
You get to name the thing.

599
00:31:14,900 --> 00:31:18,900
But calling Linux in general "GNU Linux" I think, is just ridiculous.

600
00:31:20,800 --> 00:31:22,600
I got involved in Fall '93.

601
00:31:23,100 --> 00:31:29,100
Because I was sent a copy of the first CD-ROM commercial Linux distribution,

602
00:31:29,100 --> 00:31:32,500
which was called Yggdrasi produced by Adam Richter.

603
00:31:32,900 --> 00:31:34,600
And I got a copy because...

604
00:31:34,600 --> 00:31:38,500
I had been myself writing Free Software for a long time since the early 80's.

605
00:31:38,500 --> 00:31:41,100
I was actually one of the early GNU contributors myself.

606
00:31:41,900 --> 00:31:43,800
And I was absolutely astonished,

607
00:31:43,800 --> 00:31:45,300
I was completely astonished.

608
00:31:45,300 --> 00:31:49,300
Because I've been a software engineer for nearly 15 years at that point.

609
00:31:50,000 --> 00:31:52,200
And according to all the rules I knew...

610
00:31:52,200 --> 00:31:55,900
about controlling complexity, keeping a project group small,

611
00:31:55,900 --> 00:31:58,700
having closely managed objectives.

612
00:31:58,700 --> 00:32:01,000
Linux should have been a disaster, and it wasn't.

613
00:32:01,000 --> 00:32:03,100
Instead, it was something wonderful,

614
00:32:03,100 --> 00:32:06,400
and I was determined to figure out how they were getting a way with that.

615
00:32:08,500 --> 00:32:11,900
In order for Linux to grow beyond the world of the computer programmer

616
00:32:11,900 --> 00:32:15,900
It needed a use, an application that made it a must-have technology

617
00:32:16,600 --> 00:32:17,900
That threshold was crossed

618
00:32:17,900 --> 00:32:21,700
with the development of a program that made complex websites possible

619
00:32:22,200 --> 00:32:24,600
That program is the Apache web server.

620
00:32:25,300 --> 00:32:28,600
The killer app of Linux was undoubtedly the Apache web server.

621
00:32:29,200 --> 00:32:31,100
If you look at the history of Linux,

622
00:32:31,100 --> 00:32:35,600
the adoption curve of Linux and the adoption curve of the Internet

623
00:32:35,600 --> 00:32:37,100
exactly track each other.

624
00:32:37,100 --> 00:32:42,100
1993, which was when the Apache web server project really got started,

625
00:32:42,100 --> 00:32:45,700
was also the beginnings of the popular ISP explosion

626
00:32:45,700 --> 00:32:49,500
when the Internet first became a mass market commodity

627
00:32:49,500 --> 00:32:51,900
and the idea of web-based electronic commerce

628
00:32:51,900 --> 00:32:54,300
and, and mass communication became real.

629
00:32:54,900 --> 00:32:58,100
I think it was one of the first applications that caused people to go

630
00:32:58,100 --> 00:33:00,000
"Well, if I install Linux."

631
00:33:00,000 --> 00:33:03,000
I get some tangible benefit from doing so, right?

632
00:33:03,500 --> 00:33:06,800
I mean, clearly there were a lot of interesting applications on Linux

633
00:33:06,800 --> 00:33:08,700
at, at the time, this being maybe two or three years ago,

634
00:33:08,700 --> 00:33:10,600
when the root thing really started to take off

635
00:33:10,600 --> 00:33:13,300
but there wasn't a driving, you know,

636
00:33:13,300 --> 00:33:14,600
you could almost say business case

637
00:33:14,600 --> 00:33:17,500
for someone to use Linux versus using NT

638
00:33:17,500 --> 00:33:20,800
until, I think, Apache and a lot of the things that plugged into Apache

639
00:33:20,800 --> 00:33:22,300
enhanced Apache

640
00:33:22,300 --> 00:33:25,300
I mean, when you want to go out and build.. go out to build a server farm

641
00:33:25,800 --> 00:33:27,600
It was much more cost effective

642
00:33:27,600 --> 00:33:28,200
cost effective

643
00:33:28,200 --> 00:33:33,100
real dollar returns to build it on Linux and Apache than was to build it on IIS and NT

644
00:33:33,100 --> 00:33:35,500
even if it meant that you have to spend a little bit of money

645
00:33:35,500 --> 00:33:37,100
to train your staff to learn how to use that or

646
00:33:37,100 --> 00:33:38,800
to find people who were knowledgeable.

647
00:33:38,800 --> 00:33:39,900
But the good news was that

648
00:33:39,900 --> 00:33:41,600
that knowledge wasn't very expensive

649
00:33:41,600 --> 00:33:43,300
because there were all those college students out there

650
00:33:43,300 --> 00:33:46,700
who'd been using Linux for a long time and were very familiar with it.

651
00:33:46,700 --> 00:33:49,900
If you look at the trend curves in web servers

652
00:33:49,900 --> 00:33:53,600
Apache has steadily been gaining a market share ever since

653
00:33:53,600 --> 00:33:56,100
it's up to something like 66% now

654
00:33:56,100 --> 00:33:59,300
It's steadily clobbered all of the closed source competition

655
00:33:59,300 --> 00:34:03,700
And that's because it's more reliable it's more flexible, it's more extensible

656
00:34:03,700 --> 00:34:07,000
It does what webmasters actually need

657
00:34:07,200 --> 00:34:10,000
and the combination of Apache and Linux

658
00:34:10,000 --> 00:34:12,300
found its way into a great many commercial shops.

659
00:34:13,200 --> 00:34:17,800
Essentially, Apache became the application that motivated Internet service providers

660
00:34:17,800 --> 00:34:21,800
and e-commerce companies to choose Linux over Microsoft's Windows.

661
00:34:23,000 --> 00:34:26,100
It would probably runs best on Linux and on FreeBSD

662
00:34:26,100 --> 00:34:29,700
and the reason is the communities around those operating systems

663
00:34:29,700 --> 00:34:34,100
are also the communities that contribute the most back to Apache, right?

664
00:34:34,100 --> 00:34:38,100
And there were also the operating systems that Internet service providers

665
00:34:38,100 --> 00:34:39,900
started using very heavily as well

666
00:34:40,500 --> 00:34:43,400
and Internet service providers really liked Apache

667
00:34:43,400 --> 00:34:44,800
because it allowed them to do

668
00:34:44,800 --> 00:34:48,100
a lot of different things that some of the commercial web servers didn't

669
00:34:48,100 --> 00:34:52,100
such as the ability to host more than one web site on a single box, which clearly

670
00:34:52,200 --> 00:34:54,800
if you are an ISP and you would have 40,000 users

671
00:34:54,800 --> 00:34:56,000
and they all want their web site,

672
00:34:56,000 --> 00:34:57,600
is gonna be pretty important to you.

673
00:34:58,900 --> 00:35:01,200
one of the key factors in the growth of Linux was

674
00:35:01,200 --> 00:35:04,000
the creation of companies that specialized in the distribution

675
00:35:04,000 --> 00:35:06,100
and support of the Operating System itself

676
00:35:06,300 --> 00:35:09,700
Among these companies, Red Hat Software is the best known.

677
00:35:09,700 --> 00:35:13,100
Red Hat started as a product of Marc Ewing

678
00:35:13,100 --> 00:35:14,700
while he was working at IBM.

679
00:35:14,700 --> 00:35:16,700
He wanted a little better Linux distribution

680
00:35:16,700 --> 00:35:18,100
he started playing around,

681
00:35:18,100 --> 00:35:22,100
found out he uh, he spent more time maintaining his Linux distribution

682
00:35:22,300 --> 00:35:25,300
than he did uh, than he did working on his new project.

683
00:35:25,300 --> 00:35:29,000
So he uh, sort of started the distribution himself

684
00:35:29,000 --> 00:35:30,600
He met up with Bob Young,

685
00:35:30,600 --> 00:35:33,500
who at the time was running company called ACC Bookstore

686
00:35:33,500 --> 00:35:36,900
which was a mail-order PC Unix uh, catalog

687
00:35:36,900 --> 00:35:38,800
And Bob kind of knew he wanted something,

688
00:35:38,800 --> 00:35:40,900
you know, more his own to market,

689
00:35:40,900 --> 00:35:43,300
rather than reselling other people's products

690
00:35:43,300 --> 00:35:46,400
And he was fairly good at marketing, and...

691
00:35:46,400 --> 00:35:47,800
Mark knew he needed some marketing help

692
00:35:47,800 --> 00:35:50,800
because he was very good at the technical parts, so they kinda got together

693
00:35:50,800 --> 00:35:55,100
I started working with Red Hat in May of 1995, basically right out of NC State.

694
00:35:55,100 --> 00:36:00,100
along with Eric Troan who, me and him combined make up employees #4 and #5.

695
00:36:01,000 --> 00:36:05,000
We actually reported to work in an apartment that Mark Ewing used to live in

696
00:36:06,300 --> 00:36:10,200
We took it over as kind of the development part of Red Hat software

697
00:36:10,200 --> 00:36:14,100
and stayed that way till about November of 1995 when...

698
00:36:14,300 --> 00:36:16,900
a toilet we had in the apartment kind of exploded,

699
00:36:16,900 --> 00:36:18,300
flooded our downstairs neighbor

700
00:36:18,300 --> 00:36:21,400
and she got little upset and...

701
00:36:21,400 --> 00:36:23,600
the apartment folks found out we were running a business there

702
00:36:23,600 --> 00:36:25,700
instead of actually living there the same time

703
00:36:25,700 --> 00:36:27,100
So they decided to throw us out.

704
00:36:27,100 --> 00:36:29,300
So at that point, we had about a week to go find

705
00:36:29,300 --> 00:36:31,600
our first office, which we did

706
00:36:31,600 --> 00:36:33,600
and get ourselves moved in a hurry

707
00:36:44,100 --> 00:36:49,100
We started going in again '95 or so to the venture capital firms,

708
00:36:49,100 --> 00:36:52,000
asking, saying, there's something happening here.

709
00:36:52,000 --> 00:36:54,100
There's a great business opportunity,

710
00:36:54,100 --> 00:36:58,100
to build the next Sun for open source.

711
00:36:58,300 --> 00:37:01,500
Well, the venture capitalists looked at this and said

712
00:37:01,500 --> 00:37:04,000
"Gee, you are selling systems

713
00:37:04,000 --> 00:37:06,100
the software is free. This is kind of scary.

714
00:37:06,100 --> 00:37:08,600
We're not sure that we want to put money in. And...

715
00:37:08,600 --> 00:37:12,000
by the way, we funded other systems companies

716
00:37:12,000 --> 00:37:14,900
and it hasn't really panned out. We are scared."

717
00:37:17,100 --> 00:37:20,200
I came to the US about 3 years ago,

718
00:37:20,200 --> 00:37:22,500
and the reason really was that I'd been spending

719
00:37:23,800 --> 00:37:26,800
like 6 or 7 years at Helsinki University.

720
00:37:26,800 --> 00:37:31,100
and decide it was time to see the real world and not just university life.

721
00:37:31,100 --> 00:37:36,100
Especially this area had a lot of the most interesting work being done.

722
00:37:37,600 --> 00:37:39,400
So I just decided that...

723
00:37:39,400 --> 00:37:43,400
let's try to move half way across the world,

724
00:37:43,900 --> 00:37:45,100
and give this a try.

725
00:37:45,100 --> 00:37:47,100
And it's turned out pretty well.

726
00:37:47,100 --> 00:37:50,000
[ Ah...you see this as temporary or long term? ]

727
00:37:50,500 --> 00:37:53,100
Well, we saw it as temporary at first.

728
00:37:53,100 --> 00:37:57,100
And I think it's certainly looking like it's turning into long term.

729
00:37:57,400 --> 00:38:00,900
Our youngest daughter is both US and Finnish citizen,

730
00:38:00,900 --> 00:38:02,400
because she was born here

731
00:38:03,000 --> 00:38:07,000
and the older one is speaking both Swedish and English, so...

732
00:38:31,200 --> 00:38:35,200
The next major event was one that I had directed hand in.

733
00:38:35,300 --> 00:38:38,100
I wrote a paper, called "The Cathedral & the Bazaar".

734
00:38:38,100 --> 00:38:41,800
which was my observations, my anthropological analysis

735
00:38:41,800 --> 00:38:44,100
of what it was that made the open source world work.

736
00:38:44,100 --> 00:38:49,400
We didn't call it that then. We were still using the term "Free Software" primarily.

737
00:38:49,400 --> 00:38:52,100
So it was my observation of what made the Free Software world work

738
00:38:52,100 --> 00:38:56,400
and why we were able to produce extremely high quality software

739
00:38:56,900 --> 00:39:00,900
in spite of constantly violating all of the standard rules of software engineering

740
00:39:01,800 --> 00:39:04,500
In that paper, I was setting up a contrast

741
00:39:04,500 --> 00:39:06,700
between two different styles of development,

742
00:39:06,700 --> 00:39:08,400
two opposed styles of development.

743
00:39:08,400 --> 00:39:14,000
One, which is the conventional closed development style,

744
00:39:14,000 --> 00:39:16,500
which I called the "Cathedral" style.

745
00:39:16,500 --> 00:39:19,800
In that one, you have tight specification of objectives.

746
00:39:19,800 --> 00:39:25,100
Small project groups which are run in a fairly hierarchical authoritarian manner.

747
00:39:26,300 --> 00:39:28,800
And you have long release intervals

748
00:39:29,600 --> 00:39:32,500
On the other hand,what I identified is happening in the Linux world

749
00:39:32,500 --> 00:39:38,100
was a much more peer to peer decentralized, market or bazaar-like style,

750
00:39:38,500 --> 00:39:40,100
which has a very short release intervals

751
00:39:40,100 --> 00:39:45,100
and constant solicitation of feedback from people who are formally outside of the project.

752
00:39:45,100 --> 00:39:49,100
A very intense peer review process.

753
00:39:49,400 --> 00:39:52,100
And the startling thing was that the more I looked at this,

754
00:39:52,100 --> 00:39:56,100
the more it seemed that trading away all the supposed advantages

755
00:39:56,900 --> 00:39:59,000
of conventional closed development,

756
00:39:59,000 --> 00:40:03,000
for that one single advantage of massive independent peer review

757
00:40:03,000 --> 00:40:07,000
actually seemed to win, actually seemed to get you good results.

758
00:40:10,500 --> 00:40:12,400
The reason Netscape is important is

759
00:40:12,400 --> 00:40:17,300
that they were the first large company to participate in open source.

760
00:40:17,300 --> 00:40:19,100
We had Cygnus providing support,

761
00:40:19,100 --> 00:40:21,700
but we didn't really have much business.

762
00:40:21,700 --> 00:40:25,500
And Netscape went open source essentially as a way to fight Microsoft,

763
00:40:25,500 --> 00:40:29,300
which was giving away Internet Explorer,

764
00:40:29,300 --> 00:40:33,300
but not letting anyone else have the source code, not letting companies collaborate.

765
00:40:34,300 --> 00:40:36,000
Working as part of the sales force, I got a bit of,

766
00:40:36,000 --> 00:40:38,400
I got a good idea of.. of why people bought our software

767
00:40:38,400 --> 00:40:42,400
and what it took to make our software successful in the marketplace against competitive products.

768
00:40:43,800 --> 00:40:45,100
However, the problem was,

769
00:40:45,100 --> 00:40:48,700
we were seeing, as that, as time went on,

770
00:40:48,700 --> 00:40:52,100
our software was uh,

771
00:40:52,100 --> 00:40:55,900
being competed against by other people's software, particularly Microsoft's

772
00:40:55,900 --> 00:40:59,700
and as time went on, the price of our software had to drop

773
00:40:59,700 --> 00:41:01,800
because other people were giving their software away

774
00:41:01,800 --> 00:41:04,800
at no charge or at little charge.

775
00:41:04,800 --> 00:41:07,000
Now the real problem was that they feared

776
00:41:07,000 --> 00:41:10,500
Microsoft would achieve a monopoly lock on the browser market

777
00:41:10,500 --> 00:41:14,300
and they would then use that monopoly lock to

778
00:41:14,300 --> 00:41:15,900
pervert actually,

779
00:41:15,900 --> 00:41:19,900
the HTTP and HTML standards that the web depends on.

780
00:41:19,900 --> 00:41:23,900
And once they had turned those standards in to lock in devices,

781
00:41:23,900 --> 00:41:27,900
they could then use that control to drive Netscape out of the server market,

782
00:41:28,300 --> 00:41:30,600
which was where it was making its real money.

783
00:41:30,600 --> 00:41:33,500
My concern was that as time went on,

784
00:41:35,000 --> 00:41:37,300
Netscape's business would be threatened,

785
00:41:37,300 --> 00:41:41,100
by the fact that we didn't have enough people to do what we needed to do as a company

786
00:41:41,100 --> 00:41:45,000
in order to keep our software viable in the marketplace.

787
00:41:45,500 --> 00:41:49,300
The Netscape release happened in early 1998.

788
00:41:49,300 --> 00:41:53,300
And uh, I was told later, I had no idea at the time,

789
00:41:54,300 --> 00:41:56,600
that it came about as a direct result of

790
00:41:56,600 --> 00:41:59,400
the right people having read "The Cathedral and the Bazaar".

791
00:41:59,900 --> 00:42:03,600
"The Cathedral and the Bazaar", the paper by Eric Raymond,

792
00:42:03,600 --> 00:42:09,200
was a significant influence on Netscape's decision to release source code.

793
00:42:09,900 --> 00:42:12,100
It came as a complete shock to me.

794
00:42:12,100 --> 00:42:14,300
I wasn't really ready for the thought

795
00:42:14,300 --> 00:42:16,500
that I was changing the world even by accident.

796
00:42:17,200 --> 00:42:21,200
However he was not by any means the only influence on that decision.

797
00:42:21,500 --> 00:42:23,700
Uh, and not necessarily the most important one,

798
00:42:23,700 --> 00:42:25,400
when all is said and done.

799
00:42:25,400 --> 00:42:27,600
As I said, Netscape,

800
00:42:27,600 --> 00:42:31,600
Netscape had already been talking about releasing source code for quite some time before

801
00:42:32,300 --> 00:42:34,200
anyone ever heard of Eric's paper.

802
00:42:34,600 --> 00:42:36,600
Linux Congress in early 1997,

803
00:42:36,600 --> 00:42:39,600
which was the first place that I gave that paper.

804
00:42:39,900 --> 00:42:43,900
And one of the people who heard it was Tim O'Reilly of O'Reilly and Associates.

805
00:42:44,400 --> 00:42:47,300
And uh, he thought it was pretty intriguing

806
00:42:47,300 --> 00:42:51,300
and he asked me to give it at his first PERL conference, which was uh..

807
00:42:51,300 --> 00:42:53,900
later that year, in Fall of 97.

808
00:42:54,600 --> 00:42:56,500
And apparently what happened, I was told later,

809
00:42:56,500 --> 00:42:59,000
although I had no idea that this was happening at the time,

810
00:42:59,400 --> 00:43:05,500
uh is that some people from Netscape actually heard the paper at the PERL conference

811
00:43:05,500 --> 00:43:09,500
and took those ideas back to Netscape and they kind of lit a fire there.

812
00:43:09,600 --> 00:43:13,600
The role of my paper was essentially to make the internal case at Netscape, uh

813
00:43:13,700 --> 00:43:17,700
to make the business case for why Netscape should release its source code.

814
00:43:17,900 --> 00:43:21,500
The paper was called "Netscape Source Code As Netscape Product".

815
00:43:22,200 --> 00:43:26,200
uh.. a strange title, essentially what the title meant was that

816
00:43:26,800 --> 00:43:28,000
In my opinion we needed to

817
00:43:28,100 --> 00:43:31,900
think of source code not just as something that was used in creating our products,

818
00:43:31,900 --> 00:43:34,100
but as something that was a product in its own right.

819
00:43:34,500 --> 00:43:37,200
Something that customers might use, other people might use.

820
00:43:37,700 --> 00:43:40,500
I then looked at what the business models might be

821
00:43:40,500 --> 00:43:43,400
if we released source code for our products.

822
00:43:43,400 --> 00:43:45,100
How would we license them?

823
00:43:45,100 --> 00:43:49,100
How do we sell products in this environment?

824
00:43:50,400 --> 00:43:53,600
Then I looked at the competition, particularly Microsoft.

825
00:43:53,600 --> 00:43:56,200
What would they be likely to do if we released source code?

826
00:43:56,200 --> 00:43:58,800
Was there some way they could use our source code against us?

827
00:43:58,800 --> 00:44:02,800
I used Eric's paper as an example of how distributed development could work,

828
00:44:03,600 --> 00:44:07,400
how a company could develop software not just using their own people,

829
00:44:07,400 --> 00:44:10,200
but also working with people on the Internet.

830
00:44:11,300 --> 00:44:14,900
And that's why I included a reference to Eric's paper in my paper.

831
00:44:15,200 --> 00:44:16,700
Once my paper was circulated,

832
00:44:16,700 --> 00:44:19,100
the people who read my paper would naturally enough

833
00:44:19,100 --> 00:44:22,100
find a reference to Eric's paper and read that as well.

834
00:44:22,100 --> 00:44:24,700
[ And who was involved in making that happen at Netscape? ]

835
00:44:25,700 --> 00:44:29,100
Primarily the person who made the actual decision was Jim Barksdale.

836
00:44:29,900 --> 00:44:32,000
And this turned out to be important later.

837
00:44:32,000 --> 00:44:34,800
That our big win, the big score

838
00:44:34,800 --> 00:44:38,400
that gave us mainstream visibility and credibility with investors

839
00:44:38,400 --> 00:44:42,400
came not because of bottom up evangelism from a bunch of engineers,

840
00:44:42,500 --> 00:44:45,600
but because one strategist at the top

841
00:44:45,600 --> 00:44:47,900
saw the potential power of this method and

842
00:44:47,900 --> 00:44:50,800
then essentially imposed that vision on everyone underneath him.

843
00:44:51,900 --> 00:44:55,100
When I completed the paper, I first gave a copy to Mark Andreessen,

844
00:44:55,100 --> 00:44:59,100
who was co-founder of Netscape and was at the time one of,

845
00:44:59,100 --> 00:45:00,900
on the senior management team at Netscape.

846
00:45:00,900 --> 00:45:04,900
Mark then gave a copy of the paper to several other people within Netscape management,

847
00:45:05,000 --> 00:45:07,100
including Jim Barksdale.

848
00:45:07,100 --> 00:45:10,200
I'm not sure exactly when Jim and the other senior managers

849
00:45:10,200 --> 00:45:12,300
made the actual decision,

850
00:45:13,000 --> 00:45:15,300
I believe it was in early January sometime.

851
00:45:15,400 --> 00:45:19,900
Netscape actually announced that it was gonna release the source code on Jan 22nd,

852
00:45:20,400 --> 00:45:23,900
the same time it was going to give Communicator away for free.

853
00:45:24,300 --> 00:45:27,000
When Netscape decided to release the source code,

854
00:45:27,000 --> 00:45:29,400
people sort of got a wake up notice and said

855
00:45:29,400 --> 00:45:32,900
"Hey, maybe there is something to this idea of releasing source code

856
00:45:32,900 --> 00:45:36,400
and doing development with people outside your company."

857
00:45:37,400 --> 00:45:42,200
So Netscape's decision brought a lot of public attention to the idea of Free Software,

858
00:45:42,200 --> 00:45:44,500
what became known as Open Source,

859
00:45:44,500 --> 00:45:47,000
and brought a lot of attention to the Linux operating system,

860
00:45:47,000 --> 00:45:51,000
which was one of the most prominent examples of Open Source software at that time.

861
00:45:56,500 --> 00:45:59,800
This is our first office, Mountain View, California.

862
00:45:59,800 --> 00:46:02,200
We moved here in early 1995.

863
00:46:02,200 --> 00:46:04,100
This is 4,000 square feet.

864
00:46:04,100 --> 00:46:10,700
It was an incredible leap of faith for us to move out and take the company to our own office.

865
00:46:10,700 --> 00:46:13,700
Now what's really important about this place

866
00:46:13,700 --> 00:46:17,300
is that this is the office where the term "Open Source" was invented.

867
00:46:17,300 --> 00:46:22,000
If you walk in to an executive's office and say "Free Software",

868
00:46:22,300 --> 00:46:26,100
OK, If you're lucky, the response you'll get is something like,

869
00:46:26,100 --> 00:46:32,600
"hmm, hmm, Free Software, must be cheap, shoddy, worthless."

870
00:46:32,600 --> 00:46:36,600
Uh, and if you're not lucky, it has associations with, uh.

871
00:46:38,000 --> 00:46:42,000
with the Free Software Foundation's wholesale attack on intellectual property rights,

872
00:46:42,400 --> 00:46:45,000
which regardless of what you think about the ethics of that,

873
00:46:45,000 --> 00:46:49,000
it's lousy marketing, it's not something that businesses want to hear.

874
00:46:49,500 --> 00:46:51,900
So Eric Raymond knew there was a problem.

875
00:46:51,900 --> 00:46:54,100
We'd been calling this Free Software,

876
00:46:54,100 --> 00:46:58,100
but people took the term "Free" and associated with "Free of charge",

877
00:46:58,500 --> 00:47:01,200
they thought they couldn't make money or couldn't sell,

878
00:47:01,200 --> 00:47:03,100
which is exactly the wrong concept.

879
00:47:03,100 --> 00:47:08,700
We wanted to get across the idea the software was open and that the source code was available.

880
00:47:08,700 --> 00:47:11,000
Very important pieces.

881
00:47:11,000 --> 00:47:14,700
We had this meeting at the VA offices in Mountain View, where Eric,

882
00:47:14,700 --> 00:47:21,200
myself, and Christine Peterson from Foresight Institute joined us as well as some other people.

883
00:47:21,200 --> 00:47:24,100
Christine Peterson was there by phone. uh..

884
00:47:26,000 --> 00:47:29,600
Jon "Mad dog" Hall was also there by phone. uh..

885
00:47:30,400 --> 00:47:34,300
And then Todd Anderson, who later worked for SuSE for a while was there.

886
00:47:34,300 --> 00:47:37,300
Sam Ockman who now runs Penguin Computing was there.

887
00:47:37,300 --> 00:47:40,700
He was uh.. He was an employee of VA at the time

888
00:47:40,700 --> 00:47:43,600
Well, we came up with the concept of Open Source,

889
00:47:43,600 --> 00:47:46,900
we called Linus in fact and asked Linus if he liked it.

890
00:47:46,900 --> 00:47:50,100
He was interested, He liked it.

891
00:47:50,100 --> 00:47:52,600
Eventually we came up with something that replaced "Free Software".

892
00:47:52,600 --> 00:47:54,200
That was the beginning of Open Source.

893
00:47:54,200 --> 00:47:56,300
[ How did you chose words "Open Source"? ]

894
00:47:57,100 --> 00:48:01,100
You know, I think Christine Peterson was the person who really came up with the idea.

895
00:48:01,500 --> 00:48:08,300
Uh, we wanted, again, the idea that the source code was out there and it was open.

896
00:48:08,300 --> 00:48:09,700
There weren't many choices.

897
00:48:11,800 --> 00:48:15,800
Well, since the fist three recipients have spoken for the Open Source movement,

898
00:48:16,800 --> 00:48:20,300
I think I should speak about the Free Software movement.

899
00:48:20,300 --> 00:48:23,800
The Open Source movement, focuses on practical advantages

900
00:48:23,800 --> 00:48:26,500
that you can get by having a community of users

901
00:48:26,500 --> 00:48:30,500
who can cooperate on interchanging and improving software.

902
00:48:30,600 --> 00:48:34,400
I agree completely with the points they make about that.

903
00:48:34,400 --> 00:48:38,900
The reason why my views are different, while I am in the Free Software movement

904
00:48:38,900 --> 00:48:41,000
rather than the Open Source movement,

905
00:48:41,000 --> 00:48:44,000
is that I believe there's something more important at stake.

906
00:48:44,000 --> 00:48:49,000
That freedom to cooperate with other people, freedom to have a community...

907
00:48:49,000 --> 00:48:51,200
is important for our quality of life.

908
00:48:51,200 --> 00:48:55,200
It's important for having a good society that we can live in.

909
00:48:55,300 --> 00:49:01,300
And that that is in my view, even more important than having powerful and reliable software.

910
00:49:01,800 --> 00:49:05,800
But I think some of the people in the Free Software camp...

911
00:49:06,600 --> 00:49:10,000
are a little scared by the commercialization.

912
00:49:12,000 --> 00:49:16,000
And uh, you know, of course a rebel is put off by success.

913
00:49:16,300 --> 00:49:19,900
uh.. I think that commercialization is very important.

914
00:49:19,900 --> 00:49:22,700
We want to mainstream this software,

915
00:49:22,700 --> 00:49:27,900
and I work with Richard Stallman who's the gray haired man of Free Software,

916
00:49:29,400 --> 00:49:32,400
uh, on a regular basis, and I don't feel

917
00:49:32,400 --> 00:49:35,900
I have any philosophical differences.

918
00:49:35,900 --> 00:49:39,000
me as author the Open Source definition and

919
00:49:39,000 --> 00:49:44,300
he is originator of free software as an organized thing,

920
00:49:45,800 --> 00:49:48,800
except for one thing. Richard thinks that all software should be free,

921
00:49:48,800 --> 00:49:53,500
and I think that free software and non-free software should coexist.

922
00:49:53,500 --> 00:49:55,200
That's the only difference we have.

923
00:49:56,000 --> 00:49:58,800
Uh, we decided early on that what we needed,

924
00:49:58,800 --> 00:50:02,800
a..a definition, we needed a kind of meta-license to define the term "Open Source".

925
00:50:03,000 --> 00:50:03,800
a, a definition, we needed a kind of meta-license to define the term "Open Source".

926
00:50:03,800 --> 00:50:07,600
And what we came up with is a document called "The Open Source Definition".

927
00:50:07,600 --> 00:50:12,800
It's derived from the Debian Free Software guidelines that were originally written by Bruce Parens.

928
00:50:13,300 --> 00:50:16,600
I'd written the original draft of that, uh,

929
00:50:16,600 --> 00:50:20,100
discussed it for a month with the Debian developers

930
00:50:20,100 --> 00:50:22,800
Debian is a Linux distribution

931
00:50:22,800 --> 00:50:26,000
And made it their project policy

932
00:50:26,000 --> 00:50:28,900
And Eric and I decided to relabel

933
00:50:29,700 --> 00:50:31,800
what we'd written for Debian

934
00:50:31,800 --> 00:50:33,100
as The Open Source definition

935
00:50:33,100 --> 00:50:35,400
and to say Open Source is a software

936
00:50:35,800 --> 00:50:38,300
that gives you a list of nine rights

937
00:50:38,300 --> 00:50:40,600
which is in the Open Source definition.

938
00:50:41,600 --> 00:50:44,400
The first right is Free Redistribution

939
00:50:44,400 --> 00:50:46,800
This doesn't mean Free as in no price

940
00:50:46,800 --> 00:50:49,000
It means liberty

941
00:50:49,800 --> 00:50:52,600
Um, you have to be free to redistribute

942
00:50:52,600 --> 00:50:54,100
your software to someone else

943
00:50:54,100 --> 00:50:56,300
And actually no price is a side effect

944
00:50:56,300 --> 00:50:59,600
You can charge for that redistribution or not

945
00:50:59,600 --> 00:51:01,800
It has to come with source code

946
00:51:02,100 --> 00:51:05,500
So that someone can maintain a program.

947
00:51:05,500 --> 00:51:08,200
If they go from a PC to a Mac for example

948
00:51:08,600 --> 00:51:11,600
they can change the software.

949
00:51:11,600 --> 00:51:14,000
Derived Works have to be possible

950
00:51:14,000 --> 00:51:16,700
If someone has to improve your program

951
00:51:16,700 --> 00:51:22,000
um, they should be able to distribute the result

952
00:51:22,000 --> 00:51:25,500
uh, There is a provision about integrity

953
00:51:25,500 --> 00:51:26,800
of the author's source code

954
00:51:27,000 --> 00:51:31,900
which says that the author can sort of maintain their honor

955
00:51:31,900 --> 00:51:33,700
and if you make a change

956
00:51:34,100 --> 00:51:36,400
you might have to change the name of the program

957
00:51:36,400 --> 00:51:39,100
or mark out your change very clearly

958
00:51:39,100 --> 00:51:42,500
so that your change doesn't reflect on the author

959
00:51:42,500 --> 00:51:46,300
There is no discrimination against people or groups.

960
00:51:46,400 --> 00:51:48,200
Uh, the example I usually use is

961
00:51:48,900 --> 00:51:51,400
You can't stop an abortion clinic

962
00:51:51,400 --> 00:51:54,600
or an anti-abortion activist from using the software

963
00:51:54,600 --> 00:51:58,200
There is no discrimination against fields of endeavor

964
00:51:58,600 --> 00:52:01,400
And that means the software has to be usable

965
00:52:01,600 --> 00:52:04,900
in a business as well as in a school

966
00:52:04,900 --> 00:52:08,400
The license has to be distributable

967
00:52:08,500 --> 00:52:09,500
In other words

968
00:52:09,700 --> 00:52:12,900
I have to be able to give that license to someone

969
00:52:12,900 --> 00:52:16,300
and that license then should work

970
00:52:16,300 --> 00:52:19,000
if that someone gives it to yet a third person

971
00:52:19,000 --> 00:52:22,800
The license can't be specific to a product

972
00:52:22,800 --> 00:52:24,000
in other words

973
00:52:24,000 --> 00:52:29,200
if I distribute my software on a Red Hat system

974
00:52:29,200 --> 00:52:30,800
the license can't say

975
00:52:30,800 --> 00:52:34,500
you can't distribute this on a SuSE or Debian system

976
00:52:34,500 --> 00:52:38,000
The license can't contaminate other software

977
00:52:38,000 --> 00:52:44,400
So if I distribute this on a CD with another program

978
00:52:44,400 --> 00:52:47,600
It can't say that other program must be free

979
00:52:47,600 --> 00:52:50,500
otherwise you can't distribute my software

980
00:52:50,500 --> 00:52:53,200
And then the only other part of

981
00:52:53,200 --> 00:52:54,400
the Open Source definition

982
00:52:54,400 --> 00:52:57,200
is a list of licenses that were accepted

983
00:52:57,200 --> 00:53:01,100
And the ones that we started with were the GPL

984
00:53:01,100 --> 00:53:04,200
which was actually the example for a lot of

985
00:53:04,200 --> 00:53:07,700
what's in the Open Source definition in the BSD license

986
00:53:07,700 --> 00:53:11,700
because software for BSD system pre-existed Linux

987
00:53:17,500 --> 00:53:21,300
I think the next moment that I thought was really pivotal

988
00:53:21,300 --> 00:53:23,500
was when the database vendors flipped over

989
00:53:23,500 --> 00:53:25,500
which happened about three months sooner

990
00:53:25,500 --> 00:53:26,600
than I expected to

991
00:53:26,600 --> 00:53:29,000
and actually happened in late July early August

992
00:53:29,000 --> 00:53:33,000
commitments to do one ports from Oracle and

993
00:53:33,300 --> 00:53:36,100
and Sybase and the other key database vendors.

994
00:53:36,100 --> 00:53:37,400
[ And why was that critical? ]

995
00:53:37,400 --> 00:53:39,500
because we knew that in order for

996
00:53:39,500 --> 00:53:41,800
the open source story to be credible

997
00:53:41,800 --> 00:53:44,500
and especially in order for the Linux story to be credible,

998
00:53:44,500 --> 00:53:47,500
we'd have to get commitments from independent software vendors

999
00:53:47,500 --> 00:53:51,000
to do ports of their applications to these platforms

1000
00:53:51,000 --> 00:53:53,600
and I was actually kind of worried

1001
00:53:53,600 --> 00:53:56,000
I thought that we were in a window of vulnerability

1002
00:53:56,000 --> 00:53:59,400
between the time that we announced the open source campaign

1003
00:53:59,400 --> 00:54:01,200
and the database vendors flipped over

1004
00:54:01,200 --> 00:54:03,800
that was the point at which hostile action

1005
00:54:03,800 --> 00:54:07,500
by Microsoft or other close-source software companies

1006
00:54:07,500 --> 00:54:08,800
that was the point in which

1007
00:54:08,800 --> 00:54:11,300
a serious marketing blitz might have sunk us

1008
00:54:11,300 --> 00:54:15,300
but once the big database vendors flipped over

1009
00:54:15,300 --> 00:54:17,800
that opened the way for other ISVs

1010
00:54:17,800 --> 00:54:19,700
that started the snow ball effect going

1011
00:54:19,700 --> 00:54:21,800
Every six months or so

1012
00:54:21,800 --> 00:54:23,400
I would come back to the venture capitalists

1013
00:54:23,400 --> 00:54:25,100
I would show them the new numbers

1014
00:54:25,100 --> 00:54:27,200
showing more and more people adopting Linux

1015
00:54:27,200 --> 00:54:29,000
and new people porting, new users

1016
00:54:29,000 --> 00:54:30,600
and I'd show them our customer list

1017
00:54:30,600 --> 00:54:33,900
And our customer list was getting much more impressive

1018
00:54:33,900 --> 00:54:36,500
It was people like Cisco that were beginning to appear

1019
00:54:36,500 --> 00:54:39,000
people like, you know, those dot-com companies

1020
00:54:39,000 --> 00:54:41,400
were started to show up on our customer list

1021
00:54:41,400 --> 00:54:44,000
and eventually the venture capitalists

1022
00:54:44,000 --> 00:54:46,000
you know, they kept looking at it

1023
00:54:46,000 --> 00:54:47,800
they kept saying "Oh, we can't quite do it"

1024
00:54:47,800 --> 00:54:51,000
Finally, Linus appeared on the cover of Fortune

1025
00:54:51,000 --> 00:54:53,300
There was something happening with Open Source

1026
00:54:53,300 --> 00:54:57,300
Well, at that point, the venture capitalists couldn't ignore it

1027
00:54:57,700 --> 00:55:00,600
they just got sick of hearing about Linux everywhere

1028
00:55:00,600 --> 00:55:02,500
and they got tired of me, just, you know

1029
00:55:02,500 --> 00:55:05,900
showing it to them every, at that point it was almost every week

1030
00:55:05,900 --> 00:55:08,500
So they uh, they decided it was time to invest,

1031
00:55:08,500 --> 00:55:10,300
that there was something happening

1032
00:55:10,300 --> 00:55:13,800
I announced Open Source to the world on the Internet

1033
00:55:13,800 --> 00:55:17,200
I did a lot of the early... administrative work of

1034
00:55:17,200 --> 00:55:20,700
starting the Open Source Initiative

1035
00:55:20,700 --> 00:55:22,500
and I think six months later

1036
00:55:22,500 --> 00:55:25,000
I was reading the words Open Source

1037
00:55:25,000 --> 00:55:27,600
in the news all the time

1038
00:55:27,600 --> 00:55:29,900
and was totally astounded

1039
00:55:29,900 --> 00:55:31,100
And a year later, I believe

1040
00:55:31,100 --> 00:55:35,100
Microsoft was talking about releasing some source code

1041
00:55:36,200 --> 00:55:38,400
And someone in the press asked Steve Ballmer

1042
00:55:38,400 --> 00:55:41,000
if they were going to open source their code

1043
00:55:41,000 --> 00:55:42,500
and Steve Ballmer said,

1044
00:55:42,500 --> 00:55:46,500
"Well, Open Source means more than just releasing the source code"

1045
00:55:46,800 --> 00:55:49,400
And I realized that he had read my document

1046
00:55:49,400 --> 00:55:52,200
and understood it and was now telling the press about this

1047
00:55:52,600 --> 00:55:55,600
Now if you are like just a guy on the net

1048
00:55:55,600 --> 00:55:57,900
who's not doing this for a job at all

1049
00:55:57,900 --> 00:55:59,700
and you sort of write a manifesto

1050
00:55:59,700 --> 00:56:02,000
and it spreads out through the world

1051
00:56:02,000 --> 00:56:03,000
and a year later

1052
00:56:03,000 --> 00:56:06,100
the vice president of Microsoft is talking about that

1053
00:56:06,100 --> 00:56:09,400
You'd think you were on drugs, wouldn't you?

1054
00:56:09,400 --> 00:56:11,100
But that's what really happened

1055
00:56:17,000 --> 00:56:21,000
The Local Users Groups tend to be more than an issue of

1056
00:56:22,900 --> 00:56:25,000
building a social network

1057
00:56:26,200 --> 00:56:31,800
especially getting people familiarized with the issues

1058
00:56:33,400 --> 00:56:37,600
also just acting as a kind of supporting network

1059
00:56:37,700 --> 00:56:42,900
for people who, who do not, for example, have the ability

1060
00:56:42,900 --> 00:56:46,100
to pay for commercial support network

1061
00:56:46,300 --> 00:56:48,700
So one thing they're doing in this area

1062
00:56:48,700 --> 00:56:50,700
for example, is they're making these.

1063
00:56:50,900 --> 00:56:52,700
I think it's once a month

1064
00:56:52,700 --> 00:56:56,400
They're having install fests, which means that

1065
00:56:56,600 --> 00:57:00,900
people who have problems getting Linux installed on their machines

1066
00:57:01,100 --> 00:57:02,600
or have some issue, I mean

1067
00:57:02,600 --> 00:57:04,000
maybe they've installed Linux

1068
00:57:04,000 --> 00:57:06,600
but want to set up the network in a specific way

1069
00:57:06,600 --> 00:57:08,700
can actually bring in their machines

1070
00:57:08,700 --> 00:57:09,800
to this users group meeting

1071
00:57:09,800 --> 00:57:13,400
And there's a lot of people there willing to help

1072
00:57:13,400 --> 00:57:17,400
who may have seen the same problem before.

1073
00:57:26,400 --> 00:57:28,100
Well, actually things aren't so well.

1074
00:57:28,100 --> 00:57:31,300
I tried it earlier myself. I had problems.

1075
00:57:31,300 --> 00:57:33,700
And so I came to this install fest where

1076
00:57:33,700 --> 00:57:35,400
all the gurus abound.

1077
00:57:35,400 --> 00:57:39,300
Hopefully I'll have better luck getting it in.

1078
00:57:39,300 --> 00:57:42,100
Instead of having, uh, sending e-mails, or

1079
00:57:42,100 --> 00:57:44,000
writing to news groups on the Internet

1080
00:57:44,000 --> 00:57:46,500
and waiting several days for the answers sometimes

1081
00:57:46,500 --> 00:57:49,500
it's easy to come here and find other people

1082
00:57:49,500 --> 00:57:50,700
who might know about your problem

1083
00:57:50,700 --> 00:57:52,600
and may be able to help you

1084
00:57:52,600 --> 00:57:53,700
And hopefully within a few hours

1085
00:57:53,700 --> 00:57:55,900
you have your machine installed

1086
00:57:55,900 --> 00:57:59,900
Originally I wanted to it install on uh, my larger laptop

1087
00:58:00,100 --> 00:58:01,800
and so I just did a search on the net

1088
00:58:01,800 --> 00:58:05,800
and found where there were resources to get help

1089
00:58:06,400 --> 00:58:08,100
And um, I'm here today

1090
00:58:08,100 --> 00:58:11,800
cause I'm trying to put Linux on this little guy right here.

1091
00:58:11,800 --> 00:58:14,100
just a Toshiba Libretto

1092
00:58:14,100 --> 00:58:16,700
It's not a easiest thing in the world to do

1093
00:58:16,700 --> 00:58:19,300
because it's a weird piece of hardware, so...

1094
00:58:19,300 --> 00:58:21,300
Any chairs around here?

1095
00:58:33,200 --> 00:58:35,000
I think that Department of Justice case

1096
00:58:35,000 --> 00:58:37,000
has made people aware of the fact that

1097
00:58:37,000 --> 00:58:40,000
you should at least look for alternatives to Microsoft.

1098
00:58:40,000 --> 00:58:44,000
and maybe Microsoft isn't the American dream after all

1099
00:58:44,100 --> 00:58:46,000
and that kind of shifting perception

1100
00:58:47,300 --> 00:58:49,100
you can very clearly see

1101
00:58:49,100 --> 00:58:53,100
that people just took Microsoft for granted

1102
00:58:53,600 --> 00:58:56,000
and maybe they're still buying Microsoft but at least

1103
00:58:56,000 --> 00:58:58,900
they're kind of more aware of the issue these days

1104
00:58:58,900 --> 00:59:01,600
Microsoft actually uses Linux as defense

1105
00:59:01,600 --> 00:59:03,000
They used Linux to ground a claim

1106
00:59:03,000 --> 00:59:04,000
that they don't have a monopoly

1107
00:59:04,000 --> 00:59:07,100
because Linux could essentially

1108
00:59:07,100 --> 00:59:09,000
push them off their catbird seat at any time.

1109
00:59:09,000 --> 00:59:11,800
It was a very ingenious argument, totally specious

1110
00:59:11,800 --> 00:59:13,600
because it didn't

1111
00:59:13,600 --> 00:59:15,800
do anything to answer the charge

1112
00:59:15,800 --> 00:59:17,400
that they had previously engaged in

1113
00:59:17,400 --> 00:59:20,100
bullying and various anti-competitive practices.

1114
00:59:20,100 --> 00:59:21,700
but it was clever of them

1115
00:59:21,700 --> 00:59:24,200
And, in an event, the judge didn't buy it

1116
00:59:26,500 --> 00:59:29,100
While ordinarily we in the Linux community are rather worried about

1117
00:59:29,100 --> 00:59:31,500
letting Microsoft become the issue,

1118
00:59:31,500 --> 00:59:36,700
but there was a Slashdot article about December of '98

1119
00:59:36,700 --> 00:59:42,500
where a fellow named Matt at the noodle had pointed out that...

1120
00:59:42,500 --> 00:59:45,500
the, a gentleman in Australia has managed to receive a refund for

1121
00:59:45,500 --> 00:59:49,500
the unused copy of Windows that came with his computer.

1122
00:59:49,500 --> 00:59:54,000
So he declared the 19th of January, was it January?

1123
00:59:54,000 --> 00:59:56,400
err, no, It was February. It was February. Oh, I'm sorry, the 19th of February...

1124
00:59:56,400 --> 00:59:58,500
he declared 19th of February Windows Refund Day.

1125
00:59:58,500 --> 01:00:00,800
and he encouraged everyone to go to the computer manufacturers,

1126
01:00:00,800 --> 01:00:03,800
and return their unused copies of Windows...

1127
01:00:03,800 --> 01:00:07,000
as it was specified in the Windows End-User License Agreement.

1128
01:00:07,000 --> 01:00:10,100
It's important to remember that in the License itself, it says that

1129
01:00:10,100 --> 01:00:15,000
you can receive a refund if you don't use the software,

1130
01:00:15,000 --> 01:00:18,000
and that the manufacture is bound by law to do this...

1131
01:00:18,000 --> 01:00:20,000
or it was bond by contract.

1132
01:00:20,000 --> 01:00:23,000
and we found if you called up these manufactures, they basically said...

1133
01:00:23,000 --> 01:00:25,200
"Stop bothering me kid." and hung up on you.

1134
01:00:25,200 --> 01:00:28,200
We didn't really wanna sort of giving out our location,

1135
01:00:28,200 --> 01:00:31,400
or where we were going to meet, until...

1136
01:00:31,400 --> 01:00:32,400
you know, the very last seconds.

1137
01:00:32,400 --> 01:00:35,800
What we did is, we have people meet at the place where we could control

1138
01:00:35,800 --> 01:00:37,500
in the different towns around here.

1139
01:00:37,500 --> 01:00:41,000
So I was the San Jose marshal, and I believe Nick you were...

1140
01:00:41,000 --> 01:00:43,400
I was..., Rick Moen and I did San Francisco.

1141
01:00:43,400 --> 01:00:43,900
Right

1142
01:00:44,000 --> 01:00:48,000
and so we had maps there and we handed them off everybody who was coming.

1143
01:00:48,000 --> 01:00:52,000
Well, we actually met at a Denny's That's just outside the Foster City limits...

1144
01:00:52,000 --> 01:00:53,600
Foster City city limits,

1145
01:00:53,600 --> 01:00:57,000
which meant also just outside of Foster City Police jurisdiction,

1146
01:00:57,000 --> 01:01:00,600
which meant any, any incidents that happened at the meeting point

1147
01:01:00,600 --> 01:01:02,900
happened in the jurisdiction of San Mateo,

1148
01:01:02,900 --> 01:01:06,500
and if they told us they get lost, we'd say, "Fine, we are going to Foster city. Bye."

1149
01:01:06,500 --> 01:01:10,000
It's sort of the Dukes of Hazzard method of avoiding the cops, so...

1150
01:01:11,500 --> 01:01:15,000
Well actually, originally we marched on the other side of this building.

1151
01:01:15,000 --> 01:01:19,000
We marched around and up onto the parking structure that's up there,

1152
01:01:19,000 --> 01:01:21,900
and that's where Microsoft had a reception laid out for us with

1153
01:01:21,900 --> 01:01:24,000
drinks and a big sign that said...

1154
01:01:24,000 --> 01:01:26,400
"Microsoft Welcomes the Open Source Community".

1155
01:01:26,400 --> 01:01:30,400
and the local news cameras got shots of Eric Raymond and Microsoft representative.

1156
01:01:31,500 --> 01:01:34,400
Microsoft's story seems to mostly be that...

1157
01:01:34,500 --> 01:01:39,000
...this was not an issue for Microsoft, rather from the OEMs.

1158
01:01:39,000 --> 01:01:42,300
So we all needed to go back to our computer manufacturers and try yet again

1159
01:01:42,300 --> 01:01:44,400
to try and get refund from them.

1160
01:01:44,400 --> 01:01:46,100
We responded to them saying, you know,

1161
01:01:46,100 --> 01:01:50,100
that we tried that and it's not possible, we need Microsoft to take action at this point.

1162
01:01:50,400 --> 01:01:53,000
And they just repeated the tag line over and over again...

1163
01:01:53,000 --> 01:01:56,000
"you need to go to the OEMs and manufacturers and get your refunds there."

1164
01:01:56,500 --> 01:02:02,000
We had about 150 people, probably half of which had signs and such, so..

1165
01:02:02,500 --> 01:02:06,000
Well, we ended up actually right in this courtyard here.

1166
01:02:06,500 --> 01:02:10,000
Basically we originally met, gathered outside,

1167
01:02:10,000 --> 01:02:15,000
various people sent groups in, people from FreeBSD camp sent a couple of folks in.

1168
01:02:15,000 --> 01:02:19,000
We had Eric Raymond and Chris actually tried to go up eventually.

1169
01:02:19,300 --> 01:02:21,600
They had blocked the elevator off to us.

1170
01:02:21,600 --> 01:02:22,800
[ Where are the offices? ]

1171
01:02:22,800 --> 01:02:25,000
The offices are right up here on the 9th floor.

1172
01:02:27,000 --> 01:02:29,100
We got some really nice press out of it.

1173
01:02:29,300 --> 01:02:30,500
and we think as a result

1174
01:02:30,500 --> 01:02:34,500
Toshiba made it possible for you to buy laptop without the operating system on it.

1175
01:02:35,200 --> 01:02:37,000
So, it's a small victory, but...

1176
01:02:37,100 --> 01:02:41,100
Well, even now, companies such as IBM and...

1177
01:02:41,200 --> 01:02:43,500
a lot of other computer manufacturers are allowing you...

1178
01:02:43,500 --> 01:02:46,100
now to buy machines that don't have Windows on them.

1179
01:02:55,000 --> 01:02:57,800
When I was a kid and I went to school,

1180
01:02:57,800 --> 01:03:00,100
the teachers were trying to teach us to share.

1181
01:03:00,100 --> 01:03:02,100
They said if you bring some candy,

1182
01:03:02,100 --> 01:03:05,200
you can't eat it all yourself, you gotta share with other kids.

1183
01:03:05,200 --> 01:03:10,800
But now the administration says teachers should be teaching kids to say yes to licensing.

1184
01:03:10,800 --> 01:03:13,800
If you bring some software to school, "Oh! No, don't share it...

1185
01:03:13,800 --> 01:03:17,800
...sharing means you're pirate, sharing means you'll be put in jail."

1186
01:03:18,000 --> 01:03:22,000
That's not the way society should work. We need the good will,

1187
01:03:23,000 --> 01:03:27,000
the willingness to help other people at least when it's not too hard,

1188
01:03:27,300 --> 01:03:29,500
because that's the basis of society,

1189
01:03:29,500 --> 01:03:32,000
that's the fundamental resource,

1190
01:03:32,000 --> 01:03:35,900
That gives us a society instead of a dog-eat-dog jungle.

1191
01:03:35,900 --> 01:03:37,100
[ So what about people say if that if

1192
01:03:37,100 --> 01:03:40,200
you have rampant piracy and eliminate the profit motive and...

1193
01:03:40,200 --> 01:03:42,000
...and creative works, software. Will not... ]

1194
01:03:42,000 --> 01:03:45,000
Well, they were on both counts. For one thing,

1195
01:03:45,000 --> 01:03:49,000
people are making a profit from developing Free Software,

1196
01:03:49,000 --> 01:03:53,800
but for another, the freedom to have a community is more important.

1197
01:03:54,000 --> 01:03:57,800
[ People that look at, casually look at Open Source Free Software and think...

1198
01:03:57,800 --> 01:04:01,000
Well, because you are supposed to share and do it for people's good will,

1199
01:04:01,000 --> 01:04:03,400
Doesn't that seem someone communist. What's your response? ]

1200
01:04:03,400 --> 01:04:07,200
Absolutely nonsense, it makes me really angry when people do that.

1201
01:04:07,200 --> 01:04:12,000
Well, back in, back in 1989, actually communism would have been a compliment.

1202
01:04:12,200 --> 01:04:14,600
the word people were using at that time was "crazy",

1203
01:04:14,600 --> 01:04:16,500
and I want them to use capitalism.

1204
01:04:16,500 --> 01:04:20,000
Communism is an ideology that forces people to share.

1205
01:04:20,100 --> 01:04:23,700
If you don't share, you get thrown in jail or killed.

1206
01:04:23,900 --> 01:04:30,000
In 1990, we got a visit from a director of an institute in uh, Moscow University,

1207
01:04:30,100 --> 01:04:34,000
and actually I saw him in Helsinki just 2 weeks ago,

1208
01:04:35,200 --> 01:04:37,000
but in any event, he came by,

1209
01:04:37,200 --> 01:04:41,000
and Richard Stallman had suggested that he visit Cygnus,

1210
01:04:41,000 --> 01:04:45,000
because he was interested in and understanding how the Free Software model...

1211
01:04:45,000 --> 01:04:50,100
might apply to stimulating entrepreneurial innovation in Russia of all places,

1212
01:04:50,300 --> 01:04:54,300
and we had been kind of secretive about our business plan,

1213
01:04:54,500 --> 01:04:57,200
because you know, we were'nt really sure it's gonna work,

1214
01:04:57,200 --> 01:05:00,000
we didn't want to look too stupid if it failed.

1215
01:05:00,000 --> 01:05:02,300
But I was very very open with him.

1216
01:05:02,300 --> 01:05:06,200
The more I told him, the more he started to shake his head like this,

1217
01:05:06,400 --> 01:05:10,000
and I finally said, you know, "What's wrong?"

1218
01:05:10,000 --> 01:05:15,000
And he said, "This sounds to much like communism to be successful in Russia."

1219
01:05:17,000 --> 01:05:21,000
You got to go a Gulag and end up in a mass grave with a bullet in the back of your head.

1220
01:05:21,000 --> 01:05:25,000
Open Source is not communism because it does'nt force people.

1221
01:05:27,000 --> 01:05:30,000
Carl Marx did not invent helping your neighbor.

1222
01:05:31,800 --> 01:05:35,800
It's not communist to have a commons,

1223
01:05:35,900 --> 01:05:42,600
A commons existed long before communism as a philosophy of government.

1224
01:05:43,400 --> 01:05:45,500
there are many commons in our lives,

1225
01:05:45,500 --> 01:05:47,600
For example, we drive on the highway,

1226
01:05:47,600 --> 01:05:51,000
something that is maintained for our common good.

1227
01:05:51,000 --> 01:05:55,000
Actually labeling our business model...

1228
01:05:55,600 --> 01:05:57,700
means that it misses the point a little bit.

1229
01:05:57,700 --> 01:05:58,800
whether it's communist, or whether it's capitalist,

1230
01:05:58,800 --> 01:06:02,400
the label doesn't matter, the real question is,

1231
01:06:02,400 --> 01:06:06,000
how much value can you deliver, how scalable is the business,

1232
01:06:06,000 --> 01:06:09,300
what kind of problems, what kind of of rate of innovation can you sustain.

1233
01:06:09,300 --> 01:06:13,000
and then, however you want to label that, it's really up to you.

1234
01:06:14,400 --> 01:06:17,600
The Revolution goes Prime Time.

1235
01:06:41,600 --> 01:06:43,100
A lot of people described,

1236
01:06:43,100 --> 01:06:46,000
that August LinuxWorld as "Linux's coming-out party",

1237
01:06:46,000 --> 01:06:50,000
Linus Torvalds was very funny about this, he said, "What? Was Linux gay?"

1238
01:06:52,000 --> 01:06:55,000
But some people said "Yeah, that was our debutante ball."

1239
01:06:55,600 --> 01:06:56,700
That was when the...

1240
01:06:56,700 --> 01:07:00,700
Linux Gods, and the hardware hackers really got it together with the suits.

1241
01:07:10,800 --> 01:07:13,800
At 3pm on August 10th 1999,

1242
01:07:13,800 --> 01:07:17,400
Linus Torvalds delivered the keynote address at LinuxWorld.

1243
01:07:17,400 --> 01:07:21,900
The crowds of 6000 people began lining up at 12 noon.

1244
01:07:41,500 --> 01:07:44,000
Ladies and gentlemen, please welcome Larry Augustin...

1245
01:07:44,000 --> 01:07:49,800
LinuxWorld Conference Chair and President and CEO of VA Linux Systems.

